WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.520
- The Viking longships could
average 70 to 120 miles a day.

00:00:04.060 --> 00:00:07.780
They could hit a place, raid
it, drag off whoever they

00:00:07.820 --> 00:00:10.300
wanted, and get away before
you could get your army there.

00:00:11.330 --> 00:00:12.960
That's just absolutely terrifying.

00:00:13.860 --> 00:00:17.600
- What do you think it felt
like for Alcuin and the

00:00:17.660 --> 00:00:21.020
monks to see the Viking
ships on the horizon?

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.070
- Honestly, I think it's the end of the world,
and I don't think they were wrong to think

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:28.750
that. The Anglo-Saxon Chronicle
says the night before

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:32.720
Lindisfarne, the monks saw sheets
of lightning in the sky in the

00:00:32.740 --> 00:00:36.600
shape of dragons, and this obviously
meant to foreshadow the dragon

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:40.220
ships coming up. But if you
were brave, then you got

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:44.240
taken to the House of the Dead, which
was Valhalla. Every day you would

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:48.200
fight, and whatever wounds you got would be
magically healed that night, and then the

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:51.860
next morning, you'd get up and do it again,
so you're essentially practicing for

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:55.940
Ragnarok, the final battle.
You know, there's this poem

00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:59.700
by Tennyson, Ulysses, my
favorite poem. I think it

00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:03.700
captures the Viking spirit. The last
line of it is to strive, "To seek, to

00:01:03.740 --> 00:01:07.270
find, and not to yield." I think
that's very much like the Viking,

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:11.660
you know, my purpose holds, to sail beyond the
baths of all the Western stars until I die.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:15.259
We may die, but I'm gonna do
this, I'm not gonna yield.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:21.480
- The following is a conversation
with Lars Brownworth, a

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:25.410
historian and author of many excellent
history books, including The

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:31.500
Sea Wolves: A History of the Vikings
and The Normans: From Raiders to Kings.

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:36.240
He's also the host of two
history podcast series. The

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:40.200
first called 12 Byzantine
Rulers: The History

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:44.140
of the Byzantine Empire is
one of the first, if not

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:47.940
the first ever, history
podcasts launched over 20

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:51.900
years ago in June, 2005. His second

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:55.740
series, Norman Centuries,
explores the remarkable

00:01:55.780 --> 00:01:59.520
rise of the Normans from Viking
raiders to the rulers of

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:03.020
kingdoms stretching
from England to Sicily.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:07.700
In this conversation, we focus
primarily on the Vikings, the

00:02:07.760 --> 00:02:11.760
seafaring Norse warriors
and explorers who, over a

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:15.340
period of just 300 years,
reshaped the medieval

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:19.930
world and the trajectory of Western
civilization as we know it.

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:24.720
This is a Lex Fridman podcast. To support
it, please check out our sponsors

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:28.680
in the description where you
can also find links to contact

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:31.920
me, ask questions, give
feedback, and so on.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:36.300
And now, dear friends,
here's Lars Brownworth.

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:43.920
Your writing and podcasts take us from
the Vikings to the Normans to Crusades,

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:49.760
to the collapse of the East Roman Empire,
also known as the Byzantine Empire.

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:54.690
There's a thread, I think, that connects
the Vikings through all of it, so let's

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:57.540
start at the beginning. Let's
start with the Vikings.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:02.500
So the age of the Vikings
was intense and violent,

00:03:03.340 --> 00:03:08.600
as you write about, often
dated from 793 AD to 1066 AD.

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:17.170
It lasted less than three centuries. So
the start is often dated to June 8th,

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:22.400
793. What happened on June 8th, 793?

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:30.400
- In June of 793, a group of Vikings,
probably originating from Norway, arrived

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:34.900
at the Holy Island of Lindisfarne, which
was a monastic community, and they

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.760
essentially slaughtered everyone,
burned a couple of buildings and

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:42.600
grabbed everything that had any
value and left. And that was the

00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:46.560
first Viking raid that
came in force. And I do

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:50.630
think Lindisfarne is a good beginning
date because the terror that

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:54.660
it brought really signified what was to
come for the next two to three centuries.

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:56.899
- So the word of it has spread.

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:01.700
Like there's a bunch of accounts,
like the monk Alcuin wrote about this

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:09.560
event in a letter to King Ethelred of
Northumbria, quote, "It is nearly 350

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:13.400
years that we and our fathers
have inhabited this most

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:17.600
lovely land, and never
before has such terror

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:21.360
appeared in Britain as we have
now suffered from a pagan

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.700
race, nor was it thought that such an
inroad from the sea could be made."

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:31.460
What made this race so psychologically
devastating to this monk and to the

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:36.060
many other monks on the island
and then to all of Britain?

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:40.460
- That's a great quote. Um,
Alcuin was not just a

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:44.210
regular scholar, he was
Charlemagne's favorite scholar

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:48.170
and he's largely responsible, as
much as one person can be, for the

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.900
Carolingian Renaissance that had done so
much to elevate the early medieval world.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.530
In fact, the spaces we have,
the punctuation we have, spaces

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:00.440
between words are likely
a result of Alcuin's

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:04.400
work. He was an extremely literate
man, and you can hear the terror

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:09.640
creeping into that. Um, and part
of that has to do with monastic

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:13.620
communities, the Church and the- what they

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:17.440
thought a monastic community was. So
the Church was viewed as a sacred

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:21.500
place. Everyone in Europe,
everyone in quotes, is

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:25.380
nominally Christian, and the Church
is an area of safety. It's a

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:29.400
literal ark from the troubles of the
world that you can flee to. I believe

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:32.850
there are even rules in England,
for example, that if you had killed

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.840
someone, you could flee to a church
and the civil authorities were

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:40.780
not allowed to enter for up to 40
days. So you could have sanctuary

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:44.020
there. And to violate this
would've been the worst

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:47.800
possible offense you could have
given, which is why, you know, Thomas

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:51.800
Becket's murder is so, so
horrible in England. And the

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:55.680
monks had dedicated themselves
to a life of studying the Bible,

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:59.760
to copying scriptures to
prayer, to removing themselves

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:03.680
literally from the temptations of
the world. And so they would seek

00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:07.640
monasteries that were remote, and
the most remote locations you could

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:11.380
find were islands in the North
Atlantic, because it's just so

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:15.365
difficult to get there.... So the
ocean was considered a place of

00:06:15.536 --> 00:06:19.156
safety. Not sailing on the
ocean, but these islands were

00:06:19.716 --> 00:06:24.276
literal havens of peace and
security and closeness to God.

00:06:25.076 --> 00:06:28.956
And so the fact that the Vikings hit this
place of all places you could hit was

00:06:29.015 --> 00:06:33.456
the worst, the most terrifying kind of
offense against medieval sensibilities.

00:06:33.666 --> 00:06:37.276
- So there's a kind of line that you
understand you don't cross. Like, everybody

00:06:37.316 --> 00:06:38.256
agrees.

00:06:38.276 --> 00:06:38.386
- That's right.

00:06:38.386 --> 00:06:42.276
- It's the kind of thing that there's a social
contract that most societies, most civilizations

00:06:42.346 --> 00:06:46.116
sign. There's a line that we
don't cross. Let the scholars

00:06:46.216 --> 00:06:49.776
do their scholarly work.
That's one line. The other

00:06:49.936 --> 00:06:53.756
line is more kind of from a
military perspective, from a,

00:06:54.496 --> 00:06:58.356
Mobility perspective, you
just assume the sea is not a

00:06:58.476 --> 00:07:00.216
place from which a threat could come-

00:07:00.476 --> 00:07:00.696
- Yeah, that's exactly right

00:07:00.706 --> 00:07:06.196
- ... especially the north. So your
conception of the world is shattered

00:07:06.996 --> 00:07:10.896
by, one, the brutality
that can come, two, that

00:07:10.916 --> 00:07:14.436
the sea can bring a threat, and
three, that you don't give a

00:07:14.596 --> 00:07:18.576
damn about any of the lines that
we as a society, as a Christian

00:07:18.636 --> 00:07:20.176
society, have established.

00:07:20.276 --> 00:07:24.016
- That's exactly right. I mean, even Alcuin,
I think he writes a little later on that

00:07:24.476 --> 00:07:28.336
the dead were left as dung in the
streets. So he's describing dead monks as

00:07:28.716 --> 00:07:32.536
literal dung in the streets. And, you
know, who would do this to men of God?

00:07:33.036 --> 00:07:34.486
Inhuman monsters.

00:07:34.876 --> 00:07:40.116
- So who were they, the Vikings, coming
from the north? How did they think

00:07:41.076 --> 00:07:42.756
of the violence that they were doing?

00:07:42.976 --> 00:07:46.646
- Now, that's a very good question because...
and it brings up a central problem,

00:07:46.876 --> 00:07:50.836
of looking at the Vikings, which is
the story is almost always told from

00:07:50.876 --> 00:07:54.596
somebody else's perspective largely from
the pens of those they're attacking.

00:07:55.516 --> 00:08:01.576
So they're not gonna come across well. Um,
they're often portrayed as demonic and

00:08:01.656 --> 00:08:05.396
inhuman. The Vikings themselves
though, as much as we can piece

00:08:05.436 --> 00:08:08.956
together from archeology,
from the stories they wrote

00:08:09.136 --> 00:08:12.776
later but that was another problem
there, the written alphabet, the runes.

00:08:12.816 --> 00:08:16.476
It was mostly used for spells, naming
your sword, things like that, cursing

00:08:16.536 --> 00:08:22.536
someone, but it wasn't really useful for
writing long poetry or literature. So the

00:08:22.596 --> 00:08:26.576
only Norse literature we have comes
at the end of the age when they had

00:08:26.596 --> 00:08:28.436
adopted the Latin alphabet.

00:08:29.476 --> 00:08:33.276
So it's... you can almost never see
the Vikings in their own words as they

00:08:33.296 --> 00:08:38.976
saw themselves. But we can piece certain
things together. Most importantly,

00:08:39.816 --> 00:08:43.746
Viking was not their day job. They were

00:08:43.756 --> 00:08:47.736
were mostly merchants and
farmers, mostly farmers who lived

00:08:47.776 --> 00:08:51.676
in little bays called Viks in
Old Norse, which is probably

00:08:51.696 --> 00:08:54.836
where we get the word Viking from. Um,

00:08:56.676 --> 00:09:02.096
one other note about how hard it is to- to
tease apart what's happening here is the-

00:09:03.096 --> 00:09:06.876
the English and the Frankish
and the Irish writers all

00:09:06.936 --> 00:09:10.816
call them Danes, no matter where they came
from. They didn't stop to ask, "Now, excuse me,

00:09:10.876 --> 00:09:14.676
are you from Norway, or are you
from..." So they're all called Danes or

00:09:14.716 --> 00:09:18.676
Pagans, heathen, or Northmen. Um,

00:09:18.736 --> 00:09:22.406
so this is not very helpful in
figuring out where they came from.

00:09:22.406 --> 00:09:26.336
Um, the language was interchangeable. You
know, Old Norse was spoken in all three of

00:09:26.396 --> 00:09:28.356
those Scandinavian countries. But

00:09:29.376 --> 00:09:33.176
living in the north, so far
up near the Arctic Circle,

00:09:33.316 --> 00:09:37.116
is... that's at the very limit of where technology
of the time could allow humans to survive.

00:09:37.176 --> 00:09:40.896
And that kinda, that kinda harsh
climate bred, I think, very

00:09:41.036 --> 00:09:45.736
hard people. Mercy was not
a quality they seemed to

00:09:46.836 --> 00:09:50.456
favor, value. There's a very
famous story of a Swedish

00:09:50.516 --> 00:09:54.236
Viking putting a sword in
the crib of his newborn

00:09:54.296 --> 00:09:57.836
son, and saying, "May you have nothing in
this life but what you can gain with this."

00:09:58.456 --> 00:10:00.596
I mean, I can't imagine doing that.

00:10:01.556 --> 00:10:05.866
You know, to any of my children, you
know, putting a gun in the crib, or-

00:10:05.996 --> 00:10:09.616
... you know, I'd be carted away.
But the... I think that kind of

00:10:09.656 --> 00:10:13.376
underscores the kind of violent
life that was... you could

00:10:13.416 --> 00:10:17.476
expect as a Viking. I mean, strength
was valued more than anything else.

00:10:17.716 --> 00:10:19.846
- So the understanding
of the world is harsh,

00:10:20.736 --> 00:10:24.406
and that strength is the
way you must face that

00:10:24.436 --> 00:10:28.396
world. So when you have those people,
and especially the ones that self-select

00:10:28.436 --> 00:10:31.746
to get on a boat, to face the
ocean with all the uncertainty,

00:10:32.656 --> 00:10:35.296
that results in the kind of
brutality that we got to see.

00:10:35.746 --> 00:10:39.416
- I think so. I mean, the way they would build their
ships, they were clinker built, so they were

00:10:39.476 --> 00:10:42.826
overlaid, like planks overlaying.
So they were undecked as

00:10:42.876 --> 00:10:46.836
well. And so they'd have tents. So can
you imagine crossing the Atlantic,

00:10:47.086 --> 00:10:50.446
the northern Atlantic, you know,
with these huge waves splashing

00:10:50.536 --> 00:10:54.776
over with an inch of oak
between you and the ocean?

00:10:55.576 --> 00:10:59.376
I mean, the amount of bravery that
must have taken to undergo is

00:10:59.416 --> 00:11:02.576
astounding. Plus they didn't have
a compass. They navigated by,

00:11:04.126 --> 00:11:08.016
"Where's the sun? Where are the stars?
What... are there birds in the sky? Do

00:11:08.156 --> 00:11:11.496
I see a different color of water? Do I see
leaves floating?" I mean, it's terrible.

00:11:12.206 --> 00:11:14.776
If you're traveling 2,000
miles, that's not great.

00:11:15.676 --> 00:11:18.876
So it's kind of an
intrepidness to them that

00:11:20.636 --> 00:11:24.436
I think is part of the reason why they're
so fascinating to us in our sanitized,

00:11:24.576 --> 00:11:29.736
more or less sanitized world. That
this incredible courage to do this,

00:11:30.616 --> 00:11:33.996
and some horror at what they did on
the other end when they arrived.

00:11:34.036 --> 00:11:37.026
But, you know, we'll talk a little bit
more about their religion, but they-

00:11:38.136 --> 00:11:40.106
they do not view the Christian God

00:11:41.036 --> 00:11:44.916
in particularly flattering terms.
I mean, to them, he's a weak

00:11:44.936 --> 00:11:48.856
God who won't protect his adherence, and
they can just come in and plunder as

00:11:48.896 --> 00:11:53.576
they... I mean, they'll... One Viking
famously says, "On land, I'm a Christian.

00:11:54.716 --> 00:11:56.136
When I'm on the sea, I worship Thor."

00:11:56.976 --> 00:12:00.776
It was very much the kind of
pragmatic take that the Vikings had.

00:12:01.396 --> 00:12:04.996
- Yeah. There are gods, and they
have many, but Odin and Thor are

00:12:05.056 --> 00:12:09.006
pretty hardcore gods. So everything, just

00:12:09.036 --> 00:12:12.936
their whole philosophy on life
is pretty- pretty hardcore.

00:12:12.956 --> 00:12:15.296
Probably some of the toughest
humans to have ever lived.

00:12:15.912 --> 00:12:19.241
- I think so. Yeah. I mean, their
gods are horrifying. They're

00:12:19.272 --> 00:12:26.202
polytheistic. There was no
universally accepted, Head god.

00:12:26.202 --> 00:12:29.772
I think Marvel has also
led people astray in this.

00:12:29.952 --> 00:12:31.792
- Well, we'll talk more about,

00:12:33.032 --> 00:12:36.982
religion, but since you mentioned the boats, what-
what do we understand about the technology that they

00:12:36.992 --> 00:12:40.752
were using? Can you just speak a little
bit more to this one inch of oak

00:12:41.692 --> 00:12:47.292
idea? So, these were
these long ships that,

00:12:48.312 --> 00:12:52.112
Were also able to travel
on rivers. So they're

00:12:52.172 --> 00:12:56.092
not... Like, what- what is structurally,
do we know about the boats that

00:12:56.152 --> 00:13:00.332
allowed them to be so flexible in
terms of where they can travel?

00:13:01.112 --> 00:13:03.802
- Yeah. I mean, and this was the Vikings'
great secret, and I think it's

00:13:03.832 --> 00:13:07.521
underappreciated. They built different
types of ships, obviously for different

00:13:07.552 --> 00:13:11.132
purposes, but the thing that
blows my mind is that they

00:13:11.152 --> 00:13:14.392
built these ships that could cross
an ocean, cross the Atlantic

00:13:14.472 --> 00:13:18.312
Ocean, and at the same
time, when they had a

00:13:18.352 --> 00:13:22.212
draft of less than two
feet, so they could sail up

00:13:22.292 --> 00:13:26.252
rivers that were two feet deep. And
if they came to an, you know, a

00:13:26.292 --> 00:13:31.912
block or something, 20 men could pick up
the ship and port it around. They were

00:13:31.952 --> 00:13:35.852
incredibly portable and their
speed, the speed was the

00:13:35.872 --> 00:13:37.352
most frightening thing about the Vikings.

00:13:38.112 --> 00:13:41.752
- So the... These are the same kind of
ship that they sailed the ocean on.

00:13:41.832 --> 00:13:43.932
- Yeah. I mean, it's insane.

00:13:44.212 --> 00:13:50.392
- So they're pretty sufficiently robust
to handle the ocean and sufficiently

00:13:51.252 --> 00:13:57.052
mobile to travel on rivers
and do so really fast, so-

00:13:57.072 --> 00:13:58.842
... you mentioned speed. That seems to be,

00:13:59.692 --> 00:14:02.622
from a military perspective, the
great advantage of the Vikings-

00:14:02.642 --> 00:14:07.152
... because they can move much
faster than the land armies can.

00:14:08.132 --> 00:14:12.112
So, and not just the element of
surprise, which they often had, but the

00:14:12.152 --> 00:14:15.692
element of speed was the thing that
gave them such an extreme advantage

00:14:15.732 --> 00:14:17.012
against the British armies.

00:14:17.372 --> 00:14:20.892
- That was the big one. So,
an English army, if it had

00:14:21.012 --> 00:14:24.972
access to a good Roman road that was well
maintained, which frankly there weren't tons

00:14:25.032 --> 00:14:29.021
of them, but they could average
something like 10 to 15 miles per day-

00:14:29.092 --> 00:14:32.772
... on a good day, if they didn't have a large
baggage train to slow them down. If you had a

00:14:32.832 --> 00:14:36.552
cavalry unit that didn't have to
travel with the army, they could

00:14:36.632 --> 00:14:40.432
average about 20 miles a day. The
Viking long ships could average

00:14:40.692 --> 00:14:44.612
70 to 120 miles a day. So,
they're just moving in

00:14:44.692 --> 00:14:48.072
super fast motion. They
could hit a place, raid it,

00:14:48.832 --> 00:14:52.312
drag off whoever they wanted, and get away
before you could get your army there.

00:14:53.352 --> 00:14:54.952
That's just absolutely terrifying.

00:14:56.012 --> 00:14:59.032
- What do you think it felt like for Alcuin

00:14:59.172 --> 00:15:03.072
and the monks to see the
Viking ships on the horizon?

00:15:03.972 --> 00:15:07.512
Do you ever think about trying to put
yourself in the mind of those folks

00:15:08.212 --> 00:15:09.112
and imagining...

00:15:10.472 --> 00:15:14.132
In that time, you don't have a full
map of the world, right? And the

00:15:14.192 --> 00:15:16.581
oceans are not mapped, and you have

00:15:17.672 --> 00:15:21.652
a hazy conception of the world. And
so out of the darkness from the

00:15:21.732 --> 00:15:27.072
ocean where you thought nothing can come,
comes this terrifying, this brutal force.

00:15:28.412 --> 00:15:29.472
What do you think that felt like?

00:15:30.892 --> 00:15:34.682
- Honestly, I think it's the end
of the world, and I don't think

00:15:34.732 --> 00:15:38.512
that's... I don't think they were
wrong to think that. The Anglo-Saxon

00:15:38.532 --> 00:15:42.202
Chronicle says the night
before Lindisfarne, the

00:15:42.292 --> 00:15:46.172
monks saw sheets of lightning in the
sky in the shape of dragons. And this

00:15:46.332 --> 00:15:50.552
obviously meant to, you know,
foreshadow the dragon ships coming up.

00:15:51.672 --> 00:15:57.292
I can't imagine the horror. It would
shake my faith, I'm sure, to have these-

00:15:58.312 --> 00:16:02.301
these giant men jumping out of their ships
with swords raised. And you're... What

00:16:02.332 --> 00:16:04.152
do you have? Your cross?

00:16:04.672 --> 00:16:08.032
- Were the Vikings aware of the
fear that they had caused?

00:16:08.532 --> 00:16:13.492
So, did they use fear as a kind
of weapon, or was this just a

00:16:15.012 --> 00:16:18.792
side consequence of their actions,
or did they understand and

00:16:18.932 --> 00:16:22.762
use it? Like the Mongols, Genghis Khan,
the Mongols used the fear and the

00:16:22.872 --> 00:16:25.292
terror on purpose-

00:16:25.312 --> 00:16:29.392
... to increase the chance that they
wouldn't have to avoid fights, basically.

00:16:29.852 --> 00:16:33.711
- Yeah, yeah. The Vikings absolutely
used terror. It was a main

00:16:33.771 --> 00:16:36.672
weapon in their arsenal. They would attack

00:16:37.172 --> 00:16:40.942
specifically on high holy
days like Easter, Christmas,

00:16:41.372 --> 00:16:45.202
because they knew there'd be higher value
targets there with richer clothing, richer

00:16:45.332 --> 00:16:49.202
offerings. There'd be a lot of money
available. So they were rather

00:16:49.212 --> 00:16:52.842
sophisticated, which I think is
something also that they don't get much

00:16:52.852 --> 00:16:56.392
credit for. It's like they were
just dumb brutes attacking and just

00:16:56.432 --> 00:16:59.512
destroying. But they were... It was
very sophisticated. They would show up.

00:16:59.792 --> 00:17:03.512
That's what I mean when I say Viking
wasn't their day jobs. They would be

00:17:03.572 --> 00:17:07.272
traders in say an English
port, kind of looking

00:17:07.332 --> 00:17:10.652
around. They'd get everyone's schedule,
then they would sail away and

00:17:11.252 --> 00:17:14.262
come back as Vikings, and they knew exactly
where to go. They knew where all the

00:17:15.052 --> 00:17:18.572
money was held. They knew where all the,
you know, the churches were, when to

00:17:18.652 --> 00:17:22.392
attack. They knew the entire Christian
calendar. They knew when someone's

00:17:22.492 --> 00:17:26.162
baptism was, when someone's confirmation.
I mean, they were aware of all of this.

00:17:27.052 --> 00:17:31.812
And they would... They would
definitely attack to increase terror.

00:17:32.572 --> 00:17:34.492
- One of the signs of the intelligence

00:17:36.232 --> 00:17:40.132
of the Vikings is that the
Viking Age is so short.

00:17:40.552 --> 00:17:48.872
So what happens is these explorers and
these Rough men who do the raids, they

00:17:49.032 --> 00:17:52.432
very quickly are good at
conquering and then start state

00:17:52.532 --> 00:17:56.112
building, or conquering and
then establishing trade

00:17:56.192 --> 00:18:00.112
routes and stop being the
quote, unquote, "Vikings." So

00:18:00.372 --> 00:18:04.212
basically, they just... They
conquer, and then they start doing

00:18:04.232 --> 00:18:06.992
the usual instit- build the
institutions, start a state,

00:18:08.172 --> 00:18:11.392
and now they're normal kind of nation,

00:18:11.532 --> 00:18:15.412
civilization kind of thing.
So this kind of force that is

00:18:15.492 --> 00:18:21.892
the conquering, raid, violent,
intense explorers, it's like a

00:18:22.032 --> 00:18:25.352
short-lasting thing, a couple
of generations at most.

00:18:25.882 --> 00:18:29.702
- Yeah, that's right. I mean, the
Vikings were ultimately a pragmatic

00:18:29.711 --> 00:18:33.032
people who, if it worked,
they would keep it,

00:18:33.822 --> 00:18:37.982
which is frustrating because they
disappear so quickly because of that.

00:18:38.502 --> 00:18:40.462
- With very little trace in the records-

00:18:40.722 --> 00:18:41.152
- With very little trace. That's right.

00:18:41.152 --> 00:18:42.222
- ... with very little writing.

00:18:42.562 --> 00:18:43.042
- That's right.

00:18:44.122 --> 00:18:45.402
- No time for writing it down.

00:18:46.002 --> 00:18:47.722
- No. Yes. Not doing that.

00:18:48.522 --> 00:18:56.262
- Yeah. Why were monasteries such
good targets for these early raids?

00:18:56.272 --> 00:19:01.602
- This is where I imagine myself as a
Viking and one of my ancestors perhaps.

00:19:01.822 --> 00:19:06.102
And sailing in... I mean, they must
have thought they had won the lottery.

00:19:06.282 --> 00:19:11.162
You got this rich, these rich
buildings, rich gold everywhere.

00:19:11.662 --> 00:19:15.462
Decorated books, jewels,
all guarded by old men who

00:19:15.522 --> 00:19:17.242
don't know how to fight. You just take it.

00:19:17.722 --> 00:19:21.582
- I mean, we should make clear that the
monasteries had... They were used as almost like

00:19:21.682 --> 00:19:24.102
storage for gold.

00:19:24.442 --> 00:19:28.342
- Yeah. And this goes all the way back to,
you know, the Roman Empire where, you know,

00:19:28.382 --> 00:19:32.302
think of, for example, the Emperor Augustus.
When he was writing his will, he put it in

00:19:32.342 --> 00:19:36.242
the Temple of the Vestal Virgins
as well as Mark Antony and

00:19:36.302 --> 00:19:39.162
Cleopatra. They'd all done
that because there's this

00:19:39.982 --> 00:19:41.762
additional protection of religion-

00:19:41.822 --> 00:19:45.622
... and this taboo against violating
that. And the same thing happened

00:19:45.682 --> 00:19:50.842
when Europe was Christianized.
Monasteries were... I mean, rich people,

00:19:51.962 --> 00:19:55.842
their faith had to be an active
faith. They couldn't just say their

00:19:55.882 --> 00:19:59.652
prayers and go to church on Sunday. They
would have to do something to publicly

00:19:59.702 --> 00:20:03.642
show that they were, you know, worthy
of forgiveness or, or whatever.

00:20:03.742 --> 00:20:07.642
And so they would donate
huge sums to the church. I

00:20:07.682 --> 00:20:11.582
think, you know, by the time of the French
Revolution, which is obviously way in the future,

00:20:11.782 --> 00:20:15.722
the Church is the largest single landowner
in France. I mean, the monasteries

00:20:15.762 --> 00:20:20.132
where... These, these monasteries filled
with monks who had taken vows of poverty

00:20:20.962 --> 00:20:25.502
were some of the richest places in Europe.
It's kind of a strange dichotomy here.

00:20:25.682 --> 00:20:29.522
- And then we should also say that the
Vikings, many of them pragmatic people, so a

00:20:29.582 --> 00:20:33.282
lot of them would eventually then
convert to Christianity, so you get-

00:20:33.442 --> 00:20:33.702
- That's right

00:20:33.742 --> 00:20:35.361
- ... you integrate
yourself into the system.

00:20:35.942 --> 00:20:36.241
- That's right.

00:20:36.542 --> 00:20:37.762
- In some sense, religion

00:20:38.622 --> 00:20:42.582
creates this backbone of a society that
stabilizes it, and then you create a

00:20:42.602 --> 00:20:46.482
bunch of rules about behavior, how you're
supposed to behave. One of the rules

00:20:46.542 --> 00:20:48.781
is you don't mess with
the church buildings and-

00:20:49.382 --> 00:20:49.651
- That's right

00:20:49.702 --> 00:20:50.591
- ... the religious-

00:20:50.782 --> 00:20:54.722
... institutions and therefore they
become great storage places for gold.

00:20:54.742 --> 00:20:55.042
- That's right.

00:20:55.622 --> 00:20:58.942
- And then the Vikings here
just test the system.

00:20:59.482 --> 00:21:03.202
Uh, I mean, it's the fortune
of geography for them

00:21:04.382 --> 00:21:06.262
and the fortune of their way of life,

00:21:07.322 --> 00:21:11.242
To be able to raid, to become extremely
rich and therefore this... It

00:21:11.282 --> 00:21:13.612
both spreads the terror across England,

00:21:14.662 --> 00:21:18.532
and the message across
Scandinavia that there's a lot

00:21:18.562 --> 00:21:22.862
of riches to be had. And so the raids,
that's why there's an explosion of raids.

00:21:23.122 --> 00:21:27.022
- That's right. And I think it's not a
coincidence that it happens when it

00:21:27.062 --> 00:21:30.982
does. I mean, you have both... So there's two
main theories about why the Viking Age starts.

00:21:31.102 --> 00:21:34.902
The first, Will Durant puts it, I think,
the best. He says, "The fertility of the

00:21:34.982 --> 00:21:38.582
Viking women outstripped the
fertility of the Viking land." It's

00:21:38.702 --> 00:21:41.032
basically overpopulation.

00:21:41.242 --> 00:21:44.682
Um, and then they're searching
for food. And then the second

00:21:46.022 --> 00:21:49.822
is there's this technological breakthrough
with the keel and maybe pressure

00:21:49.902 --> 00:21:53.782
put on Charlemagne's consolidation
and a little worries like that.

00:21:54.182 --> 00:21:57.462
I don't see why both
can't be true but I do,

00:21:59.062 --> 00:22:05.082
I do also think Europe... Like, Charlemagne
puts together this vast empire that,

00:22:06.022 --> 00:22:09.882
you know, fairly approximates the
Western Roman Empire. If you squint-

00:22:09.992 --> 00:22:12.362
... it looks like the Western Roman
Empire. He's calling himself,

00:22:13.202 --> 00:22:17.162
The new Roman emperor.
This will eventually

00:22:17.182 --> 00:22:20.442
mutate into the Holy Roman
Empire. But it's very

00:22:20.482 --> 00:22:24.382
much this idea that it's back.
The Roman Empire is back.

00:22:24.422 --> 00:22:27.452
He's crowned on Christmas Day in
the year 800, and the empire is

00:22:27.482 --> 00:22:35.022
back. Unfortunately, it was sprawling. It
hadn't been thought through. There was...

00:22:35.842 --> 00:22:39.702
The communication was terrible.
You just couldn't do it. And so it

00:22:39.722 --> 00:22:44.442
was wealthy and weak, and that
kind of attracts predators.

00:22:45.282 --> 00:22:49.262
By the time the Vikings crash into it,
