00:46:13.838 --> 00:46:17.668
William the Conqueror. You know, I
want Hector to beat Achilles. Never

00:46:17.738 --> 00:46:19.448
works, no matter how many
times I read it. But

00:46:20.298 --> 00:46:23.658
I was always interested in the Normans
because of the Norman conquest of England.

00:46:23.998 --> 00:46:27.678
And my I have a twin brother, and he asked
me, we were taking a walk, and he asked me,

00:46:29.158 --> 00:46:32.838
"How did Europe..." Uh, 'cause we, I
was reading about the Dark Ages at the

00:46:32.918 --> 00:46:36.638
time, the the early Middle Ages. "And how
did Europe, this kind of backwards place,

00:46:36.718 --> 00:46:40.658
become the dominant-"
"... force in the world?"

00:46:42.038 --> 00:46:46.498
And I started thinking about that,
and my answer really is the Normans.

00:46:47.418 --> 00:46:50.618
The Normans, that's the
great change between

00:46:51.458 --> 00:46:55.598
Europe as a backwards, inward-looking
place, and Europe as a kind of

00:46:56.418 --> 00:47:01.358
confident, outward-looking place.
And that change happens under-

00:47:02.258 --> 00:47:04.818
under the Normans. I mean, the Normans,
it's not a coincidence that they-

00:47:05.718 --> 00:47:07.678
they lead the charge in the First Crusade.

00:47:09.238 --> 00:47:13.218
They create the state of England.
If you look at England before the

00:47:13.238 --> 00:47:16.678
Vikings arrive, there are seven,
it's the Heptarchy, there are seven

00:47:16.778 --> 00:47:20.378
kingdoms in England, and the
Vikings destroyed all but one. Only

00:47:20.418 --> 00:47:24.358
Wessex is preserved, and they've
conquered about half of Wessex.

00:47:24.778 --> 00:47:26.927
And there's a young king.
What's he gonna do?

00:47:27.218 --> 00:47:30.858
But that king is Alfred the Great, and
he conquers the rest. And then his

00:47:30.878 --> 00:47:36.658
grandson, Athelstan, is the first man
called King of England, king of all Angles.

00:47:37.718 --> 00:47:41.438
And then they do the same thing
almost wherever they go. They

00:47:41.998 --> 00:47:44.018
help create modern
France by ripping apart,

00:47:44.838 --> 00:47:47.428
uh, Charlemagne's empire,
which was unwieldy.

00:47:47.478 --> 00:47:51.258
It looked good on paper, but it was
unwieldy. It was replaced by this leaner,

00:47:51.358 --> 00:47:54.878
meaner, compact thing. They figure
out how to deal with the Vikings by

00:47:55.298 --> 00:48:01.258
essentially building fortified bridges,
changes to their army, and so forth.

00:48:02.238 --> 00:48:06.138
The Vikings, I—I like to call it
creative destruction. It—they, by

00:48:06.178 --> 00:48:09.858
destroying the things they destroyed,
they cleared the ground for something

00:48:09.918 --> 00:48:10.778
stronger to grow.

00:48:11.438 --> 00:48:15.318
- Uh, that's brilliant. The creative
destruction engine that created Europe

00:48:16.058 --> 00:48:17.718
was the Normans and the Vikings.

00:48:18.798 --> 00:48:22.558
And then you also, you have another
book that talks about the Byzantine

00:48:22.638 --> 00:48:27.138
Empire, so you have the creative
destruction that resulted in Europe,

00:48:28.158 --> 00:48:34.098
that Europe led to this Western, quote-unquote,
civilization that we think of now.

00:48:34.978 --> 00:48:38.578
And the thing that protected
Europe for centuries

00:48:39.178 --> 00:48:42.678
was the existence of the Byzantine
Empire, the East Roman Empire,

00:48:43.258 --> 00:48:45.558
because of all the threats-

00:48:46.498 --> 00:48:47.308
- That's right.

00:48:47.308 --> 00:48:50.878
- ... That came towards Europe. This strong,

00:48:52.298 --> 00:48:56.178
stable empire that is the Byzantine Empire

00:48:56.518 --> 00:49:00.198
protected the forces from
everything that came from the east.

00:49:00.598 --> 00:49:00.868
- Yeah, that's right.

00:49:00.878 --> 00:49:01.818
- They were a buffer.

00:49:02.170 --> 00:49:06.150
- They were a buffer, giving Europe this kind
of vital time to develop the way it needed

00:49:06.190 --> 00:49:06.750
to develop.

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:14.850
- So it's—it's interesting to think that
the world as we see now was a result—

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:19.650
... of a sequence of quite
lucky geographical and

00:49:20.510 --> 00:49:25.250
leadership decisions in history.
I mean, it really does pivot on

00:49:26.690 --> 00:49:30.600
a few points of geography and a few
special leaders- ... that conquer.

00:49:30.890 --> 00:49:34.610
- Yeah. Had Constantine chosen
his side a little less wisely,

00:49:35.510 --> 00:49:36.650
the world's going to be very different.

00:49:37.330 --> 00:49:41.170
- Yeah, so Constantine is the guy
who moved the capital of the

00:49:41.250 --> 00:49:48.730
empire from Rome to Constantinople, thereby
giving a lot more focus to the east.

00:49:48.830 --> 00:49:55.630
Thereby protecting Europe from
the gigantic threats that—

00:49:55.640 --> 00:49:55.780
- That's right.

00:49:55.780 --> 00:49:56.910
- ... loomed in the east.

00:49:56.950 --> 00:50:00.860
- That's right. And the Islamic invasions
of the seventh century, they couldn't

00:50:00.890 --> 00:50:04.650
get past that choke point of Constantinople.
So they had to take the long way

00:50:04.660 --> 00:50:07.549
across Africa. You know, and
by the time they get to Spain,

00:50:08.410 --> 00:50:10.980
And conquer Spain and into,
that's the Battle of Tours,

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:14.750
you know, Charles Martel is able
to stop them, and they're, they're

00:50:15.290 --> 00:50:19.210
massively overextended. You know, I think
it's a very different story if they can come

00:50:19.250 --> 00:50:20.150
in through the Black Sea.

00:50:21.370 --> 00:50:25.460
- And all the times the East Roman Empire
almost died from all the invasions,

00:50:26.570 --> 00:50:31.150
all of those invaders would have just
conquered the entirety of Europe.

00:50:31.770 --> 00:50:34.010
- Yeah, I mean, I don't think they
would've met much resistance.

00:50:34.310 --> 00:50:38.210
- Yeah. So rewinding back,
what was the religion, the

00:50:38.250 --> 00:50:42.010
religious beliefs, the gods
that the Vikings believed that

00:50:42.050 --> 00:50:48.590
we've mentioned a little bit of? Thor and
Odin, how did they see this, this world

00:50:50.230 --> 00:50:51.170
and the universe?

00:50:51.870 --> 00:50:58.970
- It's, so the Viking gods are... I mean,
they've been sanitized, but they're quite

00:50:59.030 --> 00:51:01.690
terrifying. But their
basic conception of the

00:51:01.730 --> 00:51:05.360
universe is an eternal
struggle between chaos and

00:51:05.510 --> 00:51:09.330
order, which chaos will
eventually win. So I think the

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:13.030
best view of cosmology is
of concentric circles, with

00:51:13.730 --> 00:51:17.630
Utgard is the outer realm and that's where
the chaos is. And those are the, that's

00:51:17.650 --> 00:51:20.990
where the frost giants are,
all the monsters that seek to

00:51:21.010 --> 00:51:24.770
destroy. The gods represent
order and stability, and the

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:30.790
monsters represent chaos, and it's an
eternal war between the two of them.

00:51:30.890 --> 00:51:34.810
Um, so there are different categories
of gods depending on which circle you

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:38.760
come from. The gods don't all
like each other. They're not...

00:51:38.790 --> 00:51:42.700
Sometimes they engage in wars. Some of the

00:51:42.730 --> 00:51:46.710
most famous gods, the Norse
gods, you know, Loki or Freya,

00:51:47.170 --> 00:51:53.750
come from outside the Aesir, the main
gods. So it was kind of a fluid thing.

00:51:53.790 --> 00:51:55.650
- It's more a way to understand the world.

00:51:55.930 --> 00:51:58.050
- I think so, yeah. The thunder is

00:51:58.990 --> 00:52:02.980
Thor fighting the ice giants,
and that's what that is.

00:52:03.490 --> 00:52:06.930
- Uh, going to Perplexity. Vikings
followed the polytheistic,

00:52:07.050 --> 00:52:10.850
ritual-heavy religion centered on a
pantheon of gods and spirits with no

00:52:10.970 --> 00:52:14.810
single holy book or unified church,
and practices varied a lot by

00:52:14.850 --> 00:52:20.290
region and family. And so the major
gods were Odin and Thor and Freya.

00:52:21.470 --> 00:52:25.350
Odin was, his domain was
war, kingship, wisdom,

00:52:26.150 --> 00:52:31.610
death. Thor was protection, thunder,
fertility. Freya was love, magic,

00:52:32.630 --> 00:52:35.030
battle dead. Um,

00:52:36.090 --> 00:52:40.810
typical worshipers for Odin were
chieftains and elite warriors and poets.

00:52:41.730 --> 00:52:45.230
Typical worshipers for Thor were

00:52:45.270 --> 00:52:49.200
farmers and "ordinary people,"
and typical worshipers of

00:52:49.250 --> 00:52:51.930
Freya were women, magic
practitioners, and lovers.

00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:56.850
- Yeah, yeah. I mean, I've heard it... I think
you can break it down saying like, Odin

00:52:56.910 --> 00:52:59.750
was the elite. He's kind of
more aristocratic, right?

00:52:59.830 --> 00:52:59.840
- Yes.

00:52:59.840 --> 00:53:03.810
- He's the god of poetry, you need to read, et
cetera. Only the elite would know how to do

00:53:03.850 --> 00:53:08.470
that. A farmer wouldn't really care about
that. Wherein Thor is a more earthy god.

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:12.290
You know, you want the waves to be
less, you know, pray to Thor. Um,

00:53:13.150 --> 00:53:16.850
I find Odin, I think, most
disturbing. He's the god of

00:53:16.930 --> 00:53:21.189
madness and the god of poetry,
which, I guess those are related.

00:53:21.890 --> 00:53:22.270
- Yeah.

00:53:22.390 --> 00:53:26.350
- Um, but in battle, I mean, the berserkers,
probably the most famous type of Viking

00:53:26.410 --> 00:53:30.210
warriors, were considered to be Odin's
chosen warriors. They would show

00:53:30.290 --> 00:53:34.150
no pain, and they'd just run at
the enemy and attack with their

00:53:34.210 --> 00:53:35.910
nails and their teeth.

00:53:36.030 --> 00:53:39.590
Even if they could have their arms
hacked off, they would still keep going.

00:53:39.870 --> 00:53:43.530
Like they would just... And they would
attack other Vikings. They were berserk.

00:53:43.540 --> 00:53:44.450
That's where we get the word from.

00:53:45.070 --> 00:53:47.790
- Uh, what do we understand
the mindset leads to that?

00:53:48.590 --> 00:53:52.130
I mean, it wasn't religious in
nature. There's not this kinda

00:53:52.830 --> 00:53:56.550
ideology. It's just the way
of life and then the prized

00:53:56.630 --> 00:53:59.630
honor and intensity in battle.

00:54:00.150 --> 00:54:04.080
- Yeah. I mean, one of Odin's names
is the raven feeder. I mean, you

00:54:04.090 --> 00:54:07.530
were, by creating corpses,
which ravens feed on, you are,

00:54:08.050 --> 00:54:11.280
you're doing the work of
Odin. And, you know, the,

00:54:12.490 --> 00:54:19.490
the Viking view of the afterlife was
unique. There weren't really punishments,

00:54:20.570 --> 00:54:24.730
not really, for doing bad things.
Unless you did something really bad.

00:54:25.530 --> 00:54:31.810
Then you ended up as basically an
evil spirit, haunting your grave.

00:54:32.690 --> 00:54:36.310
But if you were brave, then you got
taken to the house of the dead, which is

00:54:36.370 --> 00:54:40.330
Valhalla to... And you were
resurrected. Every day

00:54:40.390 --> 00:54:44.900
you would fight, and whatever wounds you
got would be magically healed that night.

00:54:44.970 --> 00:54:48.890
And then the next morning you'd get up and do
it again. So you're essentially practicing for

00:54:49.010 --> 00:54:51.610
Ragnarok- ...the final battle,

00:54:52.770 --> 00:54:57.090
which you would lose. So I'm not sure.
It seems, it's rather pessimistic.

00:54:57.330 --> 00:55:00.150
- The battle's what... I mean,
it sounds like losing is not a

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:04.270
thing. The battle itself
is what matters, so

00:55:04.310 --> 00:55:07.762
Valhalla...It's a place where
you fight a battle every day.

00:55:07.822 --> 00:55:08.122
- Every day.

00:55:08.742 --> 00:55:11.122
- Unlimited food, there's
like a boar or whatever.

00:55:11.262 --> 00:55:11.782
- Yeah. Yeah, that's right.

00:55:11.862 --> 00:55:12.962
- There's unlimited wine.

00:55:13.142 --> 00:55:13.322
- Yep.

00:55:13.682 --> 00:55:16.542
- And you can die as much as you want-

00:55:16.592 --> 00:55:16.712
- As much as you want, yeah

00:55:16.802 --> 00:55:21.662
- ...and you'll be born again. And
this is the idea of the highest...

00:55:22.142 --> 00:55:25.842
This, I guess, if there's such a
thing as heaven in this kind of

00:55:25.882 --> 00:55:27.702
construction of the
universe, this is heaven.

00:55:28.022 --> 00:55:28.292
- This is heaven, yeah.

00:55:28.292 --> 00:55:33.042
- This is the highest form. This is the
highest place you can go to is Valhalla.

00:55:33.182 --> 00:55:38.902
Is fight every day, eat as much as
you want, drink as much as you want,

00:55:38.962 --> 00:55:41.382
die and are reborn the next day.

00:55:41.442 --> 00:55:47.702
And this is forever, preparing yourself
for the final battle of Ragnarok.

00:55:47.762 --> 00:55:48.342
- Ragnarok.

00:55:48.942 --> 00:55:51.642
- So this is where, this is the end of
the world, this is the cataclysm.

00:55:52.062 --> 00:55:52.872
- Mm-hmm. That's right.

00:55:52.942 --> 00:55:58.552
Odin's gonna die, Thor will die. He'll
get killed by one of Loki's children, the

00:55:58.602 --> 00:56:03.282
Midgard Serpent. Odin will
be devoured by a wolf.

00:56:04.122 --> 00:56:07.782
The sun and moon, which
are being chased by

00:56:08.082 --> 00:56:11.842
monsters, by giants, will be caught
and swallowed by the giants,

00:56:11.942 --> 00:56:19.012
plunging the world into eternal darkness.
Essentially all the gods will die

00:56:19.802 --> 00:56:23.342
and darkness and chaos will then
ensue. And then at the very

00:56:23.442 --> 00:56:27.242
end the... This is mostly from a
guy named Snorri Sturluson who was

00:56:27.262 --> 00:56:31.102
living right at the end of the Viking Age
and writing this. And he was, I believe, a

00:56:31.162 --> 00:56:34.842
Christian. So there's... I
think we're fusing things here.

00:56:34.882 --> 00:56:38.442
So then there would be a new Earth
and a new heaven and a new god,

00:56:39.022 --> 00:56:39.922
who's all powerful.

00:56:40.582 --> 00:56:44.562
- Yeah, if you think of religion
as a kind of technology,

00:56:44.682 --> 00:56:52.182
a social technology that stabilizes or helps
guide the evolution of a society, it's

00:56:52.222 --> 00:56:56.142
interesting to see what the Vikings
came up with. And do you ever think

00:56:56.222 --> 00:56:59.402
from a history, the grand view of history,

00:57:00.122 --> 00:57:03.532
how effective these different
technologies of religion have been?

00:57:04.862 --> 00:57:06.392
- Yeah, I mean, I think that's certainly...

00:57:07.302 --> 00:57:11.242
I'm thinking of the Viking
rituals. Hospitality is

00:57:11.282 --> 00:57:15.202
very important in a northern climate
where, you know, food is scarce, winters

00:57:15.222 --> 00:57:20.592
are long and harsh. And if you
don't share your hearth with,

00:57:21.902 --> 00:57:25.352
you know, someone knocking on your door, then
someone else might not share it with you

00:57:26.082 --> 00:57:30.062
and you could be facing death. So in this
case hospitality becomes a core belief

00:57:30.142 --> 00:57:34.382
and— ... you know, the idea was
that Odin would travel incognito,

00:57:35.562 --> 00:57:38.012
knocking on people's doors,
and he would remember

00:57:38.862 --> 00:57:42.682
if you let him in or not. And if you were
hospitable, he would bless you, and if you were

00:57:42.902 --> 00:57:45.162
inhospitable, he would murder you. And—

00:57:45.222 --> 00:57:49.922
... you know, I think these rituals
are obviously intended for,

00:57:50.932 --> 00:57:52.122
"How do we survive this winter?"

00:57:52.922 --> 00:57:57.642
- Yeah, how do we effectively spread the
message that hospitality is pretty?

00:57:58.062 --> 00:58:00.822
Good thing and it's
characteristic of religion.

00:58:01.282 --> 00:58:05.262
If you do a good thing, you'll be
rewarded. If you do a bad thing, you'll

00:58:05.302 --> 00:58:08.842
be punished. And then different
religions play the different ways of

00:58:09.482 --> 00:58:10.442
communicating that.

00:58:11.062 --> 00:58:15.022
- Yeah. I mean, I think also
religion gives you, it gives you a

00:58:15.082 --> 00:58:23.222
world view, right? It gives you a morality
and these are core parts of society.

00:58:24.102 --> 00:58:25.992
- And the beautiful thing about religion

00:58:27.422 --> 00:58:30.722
is it interplays with human
nature and it guides humans.

00:58:31.422 --> 00:58:34.042
But then of course,
human nature and humans

00:58:35.162 --> 00:58:41.342
project themselves onto the religion,
sometimes they use their religion. It's

00:58:42.562 --> 00:58:46.502
to accomplish goals in a pragmatic sense, in
a political sense, in a geopolitical sense,

00:58:46.562 --> 00:58:52.842
in a military sense, in a social
sense. And so there's that dance of

00:58:54.202 --> 00:58:57.942
how religion invigorates
and guides the peoples,

00:58:58.522 --> 00:59:05.062
and then how the peoples use the religion
to guide the direction of the world.

00:59:06.082 --> 00:59:10.062
And that's certainly the history of
Christianity has a big role to play in

00:59:10.102 --> 00:59:13.562
the history of Europe, in the
history of the Byzantine Empire,

00:59:14.202 --> 00:59:18.002
And that part of the world. And it
was an incredibly effective religion,

00:59:18.782 --> 00:59:22.302
Once Constantine converted.

00:59:23.182 --> 00:59:26.602
It spread extremely quickly, relatively
speaking, across a couple of

00:59:26.641 --> 00:59:30.442
centuries. Just to linger
on the Viking views of the

00:59:30.482 --> 00:59:34.352
world and the afterlife. So we
mentioned Valhalla. There's the Norns,

00:59:34.402 --> 00:59:38.002
which are the three spirits that
represent the past, the present and the

00:59:38.042 --> 00:59:43.682
necessity. They spin the fates of all
men and gods at the Roots of Yggdrasil.

00:59:44.042 --> 00:59:45.342
- Yeah. Yggdrasil.

00:59:45.402 --> 00:59:49.372
- Yggdrasil. So there's a notion
of like determinism and fate

00:59:50.482 --> 00:59:55.422
to the Viking life. And there's
Valhalla, there's Hel, Niflheim.

00:59:55.682 --> 00:59:58.281
This was the destination for
the vast majority of people.

00:59:58.322 --> 01:00:01.762
So if you don't make it to
Valhalla, this is where you go.

01:00:01.862 --> 01:00:02.112
- That's where you go.

01:00:02.142 --> 01:00:05.882
- Unless you're a real bad person, then there's
some punishment for the truly wicked.

01:00:06.422 --> 01:00:11.862
- And we should point out that Hel, spelled
with one L was a daughter of Loki-

01:00:12.082 --> 01:00:15.602
... And was not the same as the...

01:00:15.702 --> 01:00:16.252
- Hel with the two L's.

01:00:16.302 --> 01:00:17.822
- Hel with the two L's. Very different.

01:00:18.622 --> 01:00:20.962
- It's more like purgatory
type of situation.

01:00:20.972 --> 01:00:24.502
- Yeah, so it's the house of the, it's like the
house of the dead, the house of the underworld.

01:00:24.512 --> 01:00:28.242
- A colorless twilight, not necessarily
a place of punishment but

01:00:28.302 --> 01:00:32.262
simply the inevitable end for most, unless

01:00:32.322 --> 01:00:35.522
you end up in Valhalla, which means
you're a great warrior dying in battle.

01:00:36.082 --> 01:00:39.922
- It reminds me of the Greek view of the afterlife, right?
Where you essentially get amnesia and forget who you

01:00:40.022 --> 01:00:43.992
are unless someone makes a sacrifice
and says your name, and only

01:00:44.042 --> 01:00:48.042
then you'll remember it. So
your destiny is ultimately to

01:00:49.022 --> 01:00:52.722
just become gray and fade
away. So you might as well-

01:00:53.222 --> 01:00:55.742
you might as well be brave. You
might as well run at that spear.

01:00:56.702 --> 01:00:59.562
- So that was the engine of their-

01:01:00.322 --> 01:01:04.072
the warrior culture that
was core to their society.

01:01:04.842 --> 01:01:06.482
- I think probably.

01:01:06.562 --> 01:01:10.482
- I have to ask about Vikings as explorers.
They were...... truly one of the greatest

01:01:10.542 --> 01:01:13.362
explorers in history. What can you say to,

01:01:14.182 --> 01:01:18.002
what is it in their spirit that motivated
them? I mean, they sailed, they

01:01:18.062 --> 01:01:22.052
reached North America 500 years
before Columbus. They sailed,

01:01:23.522 --> 01:01:29.822
Obviously to England, Spain, Italy, Russia,
North Africa, the Middle East, Paris,

01:01:30.692 --> 01:01:34.462
and I'm just showing here a map
of the ocean routes and the river

01:01:34.482 --> 01:01:39.842
systems that they connected to and
sailed. What do you think drove them

01:01:40.702 --> 01:01:41.982
