01:06:31.262 --> 01:06:35.022
Tell the story of his journey.
What do we know about him?

01:06:35.442 --> 01:06:40.302
- So let's begin with his dad. His
dad's name is Erik the Red, who

01:06:41.262 --> 01:06:44.942
was forced to flee Norway when
he was probably 10 years old

01:06:45.082 --> 01:06:48.992
because his dad had killed some
people. It's kind of hilarious.

01:06:49.062 --> 01:06:53.422
In the saga it says,
"For a few killings..."

01:06:53.962 --> 01:06:57.172
Okay, I guess that's a
thing. So he went to Iceland

01:06:58.182 --> 01:07:01.122
and he got a farm in Iceland which
was already starting to become

01:07:01.202 --> 01:07:04.562
overpopulated. They had cut
down all the trees. There were

01:07:04.572 --> 01:07:08.522
some climate problems of deforestation

01:07:08.542 --> 01:07:12.162
and farms just blowing
away, so the population was

01:07:12.182 --> 01:07:16.018
essentially beginning to
crash in Iceland. And he

01:07:16.058 --> 01:07:20.678
got into a fight with his neighbor
and ended up killing his neighbor,

01:07:21.778 --> 01:07:25.698
and so he was exiled from Iceland. He was exiled
from the place his father had been exiled

01:07:25.738 --> 01:07:25.938
from.

01:07:26.718 --> 01:07:29.118
- So it runs in the family,
this whole outlaw thing.

01:07:29.598 --> 01:07:33.348
- What also ran in the family
apparently was this streak, this

01:07:33.438 --> 01:07:36.928
courageous streak. And he had heard
that there had been people... So the,

01:07:37.618 --> 01:07:41.108
the Norwegian Vikings, they
were aiming for England, and

01:07:41.158 --> 01:07:44.548
they hit the Hebrides, which are
these kind of treeless islands

01:07:45.118 --> 01:07:49.038
above Scotland, and they found they were
good for refueling 'cause they'd get,

01:07:49.178 --> 01:07:52.718
pick up water or whatever, and then
on your way to Scotland to raid.

01:07:53.418 --> 01:07:57.278
And then a Viking had missed
the Hebrides and discovered

01:07:57.398 --> 01:08:01.298
Iceland, and then another
Viking had aimed for

01:08:01.398 --> 01:08:05.298
Iceland, missed, and hit
Greenland. And a little fun

01:08:05.378 --> 01:08:09.138
fact about Greenland, it is both
north, south, east, and west of

01:08:09.198 --> 01:08:12.078
Iceland. So it's any direction,
you're gonna hit Greenland.

01:08:12.798 --> 01:08:14.898
- So Greenland is hard to miss.

01:08:15.068 --> 01:08:18.818
- It's hard to miss, which is not
to take away anything from the

01:08:18.878 --> 01:08:22.868
extraordinary danger, the certain
death of going further west. But

01:08:22.878 --> 01:08:26.678
there was this... By this time, there was
this idea that, you know, enough people

01:08:26.698 --> 01:08:30.038
had become famous by sailing
west into the unknown and

01:08:30.098 --> 01:08:33.938
discovering things, that I think there was a
general idea of there's more out there to the

01:08:34.008 --> 01:08:39.028
west. And so he had talked to
someone who had seen Greenland and

01:08:39.038 --> 01:08:42.978
reported that there was this
good land further west. And so

01:08:43.038 --> 01:08:47.418
he hired the ship's crew of that Viking.
So it's kind of the deck was loaded,

01:08:48.318 --> 01:08:51.618
and he went to Greenland where he was able

01:08:51.658 --> 01:08:55.438
to settle two different colonies. One
was called the Western Settlement

01:08:55.598 --> 01:08:58.698
in the west, and one was called the Eastern
Settlement in essentially the extreme south.

01:08:59.318 --> 01:09:03.018
And that was essentially the edges
of where Viking technology could be.

01:09:03.938 --> 01:09:07.878
A cool factoid is that the
Vikings practiced husbandry,

01:09:08.458 --> 01:09:10.838
raised animals, and obviously
this is not an option

01:09:11.738 --> 01:09:15.658
in Greenland, although they couldn't have known
it at the time. But they brought plants with

01:09:15.718 --> 01:09:20.858
them. So, and then they were able to
trade with the native Inuit for walrus

01:09:20.958 --> 01:09:24.718
blubber and things like that,
and they made a go of it. But

01:09:25.218 --> 01:09:28.678
what's obvious, you know,
anyone who's seen Greenland,

01:09:29.218 --> 01:09:33.038
there's, there are no trees. It's
almost impossible to survive

01:09:33.658 --> 01:09:37.098
by practicing husbandry. It is
impossible to survive, as it turns out,

01:09:37.598 --> 01:09:41.438
just practicing husbandry. And
by this point, I think this

01:09:41.498 --> 01:09:46.898
extraordinary Viking pragmatism is
beginning to be played out. Because

01:09:47.898 --> 01:09:54.898
one of the reasons the Greenland experiment
fails ultimately in 300 years is they

01:09:55.438 --> 01:10:00.688
fail to adapt. It's clearly they
should, they should focus more on

01:10:00.738 --> 01:10:07.108
fishing, on other sources than, than
just raising pigs and cows. But-

01:10:07.378 --> 01:10:09.218
- Oh, so we hit the limit of the,

01:10:10.078 --> 01:10:14.828
the Viking adaptability which they have
demonstrated throughout the world, I'd say.

01:10:14.858 --> 01:10:15.198
Interesting.

01:10:15.518 --> 01:10:18.998
- So Erik the Red is this, he
makes his name by exploring,

01:10:19.298 --> 01:10:24.698
and he does in fact, once he discovers
Greenland, he calls it green.

01:10:25.628 --> 01:10:29.558
He says there's so many salmon in the
rivers of, in the fjords that you can

01:10:29.598 --> 01:10:32.258
just scoop them out with your
hands. You don't even have to fish.

01:10:32.358 --> 01:10:33.018
- Was this real?

01:10:33.338 --> 01:10:34.018
- It's a lie.

01:10:34.098 --> 01:10:34.468
- Okay.

01:10:34.688 --> 01:10:35.228
- That's not true at all.

01:10:35.248 --> 01:10:36.248
- So he's doing propaganda.

01:10:36.578 --> 01:10:37.258
- He's doing propaganda.

01:10:37.288 --> 01:10:40.828
- So is that... Is this story true that he
called it green just so he can attract-

01:10:41.058 --> 01:10:41.508
- It is.

01:10:41.618 --> 01:10:41.628
- So-

01:10:41.738 --> 01:10:45.618
- The greatest real estate
scam in history. Yeah.

01:10:46.058 --> 01:10:49.918
- Okay. Genius. I mean,
just stuck to this day.

01:10:50.218 --> 01:10:52.698
- Yeah. It's the most misnamed
place in the world.

01:10:53.138 --> 01:10:56.778
But in the Europe of the
time, even in Iceland, the

01:10:56.818 --> 01:11:00.578
dream was to have land. I mean,
land equaled wealth in Europe.

01:11:00.678 --> 01:11:04.438
And here he says there's enough
land for the taking, like

01:11:04.518 --> 01:11:07.918
anyone who wants it, which is true. It's
the largest island on earth. I mean, it's,

01:11:08.378 --> 01:11:11.018
it's unusable, but it
should be called Iceland,

01:11:11.858 --> 01:11:15.738
Glacier Land or something. But
it worked. He took 500 men

01:11:15.938 --> 01:11:19.638
with him from Iceland. It's gotta
be a significant chunk of the

01:11:19.678 --> 01:11:23.478
population, but there's enough people, kind
of land hungry, there's no more room in

01:11:23.538 --> 01:11:31.468
Iceland. It's too restrictive. We're gonna
go further west. So he takes 25 ships and

01:11:31.518 --> 01:11:40.408
then 14 make it, which is pretty good.
And then those 14 ships with their

01:11:41.538 --> 01:11:46.838
300 or so people start the
western colony. And then word

01:11:46.878 --> 01:11:51.978
gets back to Norway, but Norway's 2,000
miles away, 2,000-plus miles away. So it's,

01:11:52.838 --> 01:11:56.818
you know, contact... They're having to get
resupplied. In the first winter, all their

01:11:56.878 --> 01:12:00.728
cattle die. That's not a great,
that's not a great start for

01:12:01.098 --> 01:12:04.778
people who practice husbandry. So they've
got to get resupplied from Norway,

01:12:04.818 --> 01:12:08.698
but, you know, the chances of making
it to Norway and back are actually

01:12:08.798 --> 01:12:11.698
not that great if you're
sailing without a compass.

01:12:11.718 --> 01:12:15.478
You're just kind of hoping. But they
do it. They do it. And the colonies

01:12:15.518 --> 01:12:20.018
survive until the 1400s,
where they just go silent.

01:12:20.778 --> 01:12:24.358
- So let's talk about Erik the
Red's son, Leif Erikson.

01:12:25.198 --> 01:12:27.258
How does the journey continue west?

01:12:28.258 --> 01:12:32.058
- So Erik is getting a little older.
The Greenland settlements are

01:12:32.098 --> 01:12:35.838
becoming filled up. Erik is happy where
he is. He's been kicked out of enough

01:12:35.958 --> 01:12:39.758
places. He's made his home here, and
this is where he wants to be. But

01:12:39.818 --> 01:12:43.138
his son... They're running out
of resources. There's no wood.

01:12:43.738 --> 01:12:47.358
You know, there's limited food, et
cetera, et cetera. And so his son

01:12:47.438 --> 01:12:51.408
proposes going west because he's
heard stories that there are

01:12:51.478 --> 01:12:55.048
other lands. So another Viking had
gotten lost, aimed for Greenland and

01:12:55.098 --> 01:12:58.538
missed, and had seen
something. He said he saw

01:12:58.618 --> 01:13:02.448
clouds and mountains and there's
land there. And then he had

01:13:02.498 --> 01:13:06.458
turned around. And Leif again did the
same thing, he hired the man's crew.

01:13:07.078 --> 01:13:11.018
He asked his dad to come, his dad wouldn't.
He went with his half sister Freydis, who

01:13:11.058 --> 01:13:14.638
was a whole nother story by
herself, and a bunch of other

01:13:14.738 --> 01:13:18.058
colonists, and they went,
and they landed in a place.

01:13:18.818 --> 01:13:22.786
He called it Vinland because he found-...

01:13:23.006 --> 01:13:26.666
things that he could ferment. So, of
course, the Vikings, they made wine, or a

01:13:26.706 --> 01:13:31.296
wine-like alcohol. So Leif Erikson is,
he's landed. He doesn't know this, but

01:13:32.446 --> 01:13:39.976
he's landed on a new continent with
essentially inexhaustible stores of food and

01:13:40.566 --> 01:13:43.626
timber and everything he
needs. It's the perfect place.

01:13:43.996 --> 01:13:47.766
Unfortunately for him,
it's also inhabited by

01:13:47.886 --> 01:13:51.486
some natives, probably the
Algonquin tribe. He calls them

01:13:52.086 --> 01:13:55.986
the Skraelings, which is just
Norse for screechers because he

01:13:56.046 --> 01:13:59.626
can't understand their language. They
just yell at them and attack immediately.

01:14:00.686 --> 01:14:04.746
They stay there for three
years and then give up

01:14:05.746 --> 01:14:08.846
and go back home. So ultimately, it... and
then really don't tell anyone about it.

01:14:08.886 --> 01:14:10.686
They just keep it in their northern sagas.

01:14:11.266 --> 01:14:14.926
- Why do you think they left? Why do you
think they didn't stick around longer?

01:14:15.646 --> 01:14:19.246
- I think there are a number of things working against them.
Of course, I would like to believe there's an alternate

01:14:19.346 --> 01:14:22.806
history where the Vikings
successfully make it down,

01:14:23.426 --> 01:14:27.406
you know, maybe down to Maryland or
something, and there's an alternate history

01:14:27.506 --> 01:14:31.216
of the US and Canada here, but I
think there's a number of things

01:14:31.246 --> 01:14:34.986
working against them. The
first is they stubbornly

01:14:35.026 --> 01:14:38.416
refused to give up husbandry, so
they're trying to make this work.

01:14:39.586 --> 01:14:43.406
L'Anse aux Meadows I think is where they
were, in Newfoundland. It doesn't work.

01:14:44.026 --> 01:14:47.976
The climate's too cold. It's not...
the grasses aren't appropriate, you

01:14:48.006 --> 01:14:51.986
know, it's just not gonna work and
they do not adapt, number one. Number

01:14:52.046 --> 01:14:55.526
two, they're 2,000-plus miles
away from Norway and getting

01:14:55.546 --> 01:14:59.446
resupplied, and although they are
extremely good sailors and explorers

01:14:59.466 --> 01:15:01.506
and traders, I think this
is a little too far.

01:15:02.686 --> 01:15:05.866
And then thirdly is the native
resistance. It's just too

01:15:06.366 --> 01:15:10.606
incessant. They are outnumbered,
you know, millions to one.

01:15:11.366 --> 01:15:13.756
And the Algonquin do not
want them there. It's clear,

01:15:15.046 --> 01:15:17.225
and they're not gonna stop attacking.

01:15:18.266 --> 01:15:21.046
- It's so fascinating because
they really didn't understand

01:15:22.546 --> 01:15:25.746
the full scale of the land
they've encountered, right?

01:15:25.846 --> 01:15:29.826
- That's right. That's right. I mean,
had they known, had he known-

01:15:29.926 --> 01:15:30.676
... what he had found-

01:15:30.766 --> 01:15:33.675
- That there's more south.
Maybe they, their intuition-

01:15:33.725 --> 01:15:33.735
- That's right.

01:15:33.735 --> 01:15:39.046
- ... was like there's not... it's
just all northern land, it's void of

01:15:39.126 --> 01:15:42.646
resources. We can't do the
whole husbandry thing.

01:15:43.326 --> 01:15:45.686
But you would think they
could go down the coast.

01:15:46.026 --> 01:15:49.366
- I mean, if they could have gotten
enough people from Norway,

01:15:50.226 --> 01:15:53.675
you know, or Iceland or whatever,
you know, a sizable enough colony,

01:15:54.146 --> 01:15:58.696
and build some kind of defenses to
fight off the incessant attacks-

01:15:58.696 --> 01:16:02.186
... then I think that's the difference there,
'cause there certainly the resources are all there.

01:16:02.346 --> 01:16:05.686
- Mm-hmm. Or just keep staying in the
water, keep going down the coast-

01:16:05.806 --> 01:16:06.076
- Yeah. Yeah.

01:16:06.076 --> 01:16:09.746
- ... not necessarily camp out until,
until you get further south.

01:16:10.466 --> 01:16:13.916
It is fascinating to think about that
alternate history where they would have

01:16:14.086 --> 01:16:17.946
discovered America and
settled there. So this is 500

01:16:18.046 --> 01:16:19.436
years before Columbus. There's...

01:16:20.806 --> 01:16:22.846
first of all, they could have
done a lot of the stuff we

01:16:23.946 --> 01:16:25.926
think about the European nations doing,

01:16:26.886 --> 01:16:30.846
including brutality towards the
natives. But there could have been

01:16:30.946 --> 01:16:36.466
a coexistence also, and some
of the diseases that come with

01:16:36.526 --> 01:16:43.086
them could have done the damage that
they did 500 years later. But now,

01:16:44.866 --> 01:16:50.186
it would have stabilized the populations
to where the Europeans, the French, the

01:16:50.246 --> 01:16:54.026
Spanish, and so on who come, the
natives would be more ready. So

01:16:54.246 --> 01:16:56.876
they would... Europe would then encounter

01:16:57.706 --> 01:17:01.366
a sizable population of the
Viking descendants and the

01:17:01.466 --> 01:17:05.446
natives to where the two
could hold onto the land

01:17:06.166 --> 01:17:09.136
and bring a different kind
of civilization there.

01:17:09.146 --> 01:17:12.406
Because ultimately Europe, with
the European ways, of the Western

01:17:12.466 --> 01:17:15.186
civilization, expanded
out into North America,

01:17:16.346 --> 01:17:21.946
but there could be this whole Scandinavian
vibe- ... that would have taken over.

01:17:22.246 --> 01:17:26.106
- Just a hair's breadth. My favorite
museum in New York is called The

01:17:26.206 --> 01:17:31.766
Cloisters. It's part of the Met, and in
the Cloisters, there's an ivory cross.

01:17:32.996 --> 01:17:38.426
And the ivory cross has been richly
carved with Christian scenes.

01:17:39.326 --> 01:17:43.986
It was carved in England, but
it's made of walrus ivory,

01:17:45.026 --> 01:17:47.786
and they got it from the New World.

01:17:49.066 --> 01:17:53.046
And the Viking, you know, Viking traders.
It represents, you know, the great

01:17:53.106 --> 01:17:58.026
arc of the northern trade. So it's
walrus ivory from the New World via

01:17:58.866 --> 01:18:03.546
Norway to England to New York.
It's a great symbol of that trade.

01:18:04.326 --> 01:18:10.066
- This whole just period of
thousands of years of exploration

01:18:11.046 --> 01:18:16.086
that we no longer can do, so it's kind
of geographic exploration of the world,

01:18:16.886 --> 01:18:22.166
is fascinating. It takes true
courage. It takes true wander.

01:18:22.326 --> 01:18:26.316
Uh, the kind of exploration we could do now
is more in the scientific realm and the realm

01:18:26.326 --> 01:18:30.136
of ideas and then maybe in terms
of geography out into space and

01:18:30.186 --> 01:18:32.146
exploring the universe.

01:18:32.206 --> 01:18:36.196
- Yeah, I think the closest analog is
probably Mars, right? I mean, what would

01:18:36.206 --> 01:18:40.165
it take for you to be like, "All right, I'm
gonna leave and I'm gonna go to Mars"? You're,

01:18:40.206 --> 01:18:43.866
never coming back. There's nothing
there as far as you know. You know, all

01:18:43.906 --> 01:18:47.786
the accoutrements of civilization are
not there. It's- that's the kind of

01:18:47.846 --> 01:18:48.866
courage you would have taken.

01:18:49.586 --> 01:18:53.526
- Yeah, but there's, on top of that, with
Greenland, with Iceland, with Finland,

01:18:54.586 --> 01:18:58.466
there's just so much uncertainty,
like literally what's beyond

01:18:58.526 --> 01:19:02.046
this hill. So with Mars,
everything is mapped. So,

01:19:02.266 --> 01:19:06.646
so it's really you, you understand
the full harshness of the situation.

01:19:06.666 --> 01:19:07.696
- Of what you're gonna face, yeah.

01:19:07.806 --> 01:19:11.026
- So it's more, it's that's more akin
to like, all right, I'm running an

01:19:11.086 --> 01:19:13.626
ultra-marathon. I
understand the challenge.

01:19:14.446 --> 01:19:18.086
I think more akin would be
like traveling out into

01:19:19.386 --> 01:19:22.766
like the Oort Cloud, like
beyond the solar system.

01:19:22.906 --> 01:19:25.726
- What's scarier, the known or the unknown?

01:19:26.462 --> 01:19:30.062
- I think that deeply, the human
nature pulls us towards the unknown.

01:19:30.642 --> 01:19:31.402
- No, it's true. Yeah.

01:19:31.802 --> 01:19:34.642
- All right. Speaking of
which, going to the East.

01:19:36.142 --> 01:19:40.082
So like we mentioned, the Vikings
really went all over. And one of

01:19:40.142 --> 01:19:44.132
the directions they went that ended
up touching the Byzantine Empire in

01:19:44.202 --> 01:19:48.502
Constantinople, is they went
East. What can you say about the

01:19:49.582 --> 01:19:56.682
8th century journey East in the river
networks that the Vikings did, the Swedish

01:19:56.702 --> 01:20:01.862
Vikings, the Varangians, as they began
to explore the river systems of Russia?

01:20:02.682 --> 01:20:04.982
- So this was the most surprising
part for me when I was

01:20:05.822 --> 01:20:09.562
first thinking about writing the book
and, you know, discovering where the

01:20:09.602 --> 01:20:13.582
Vikings went. I never... In a million years,
it would've never occurred to me that the

01:20:13.862 --> 01:20:17.662
Vikings went East. But a- a
good way to think of this is

01:20:18.042 --> 01:20:21.882
the Vikings launched themselves in
whatever direction their country is

01:20:21.942 --> 01:20:25.832
facing. So Sweden goes
to the East, Denmark

01:20:25.882 --> 01:20:29.602
goes down toward Germany, and
Norway goes England and the New

01:20:29.682 --> 01:20:33.902
World. So there's a Viking
named Rorik who goes East

01:20:35.062 --> 01:20:41.322
and manages to set up an encampment
on this lake called Staraya Ladoga.

01:20:41.842 --> 01:20:45.802
- Which is a launchpad to both the
Volga River and the Dnieper River.

01:20:46.342 --> 01:20:50.102
- Yeah, and these are major river systems
in the East that take you all the way

01:20:50.122 --> 01:20:53.962
down to the Black Sea and the
Caspian Sea. Because the Vikings,

01:20:54.282 --> 01:20:57.802
you know, such sea-born people,
they can sail up rivers.

01:20:58.242 --> 01:21:02.102
This allows them access
to the caliphates in the

01:21:02.162 --> 01:21:05.982
East and to the Byzantium Empire, where

01:21:06.022 --> 01:21:09.762
they, being Vikings, immediately
decide to attack the city.

01:21:11.002 --> 01:21:16.382
The Byzantines essentially set the Sea of
Marmara outside of Constantinople on fire-

01:21:16.452 --> 01:21:20.002
... and burn up all the Viking
ships. So then the Vikings decide,

01:21:20.522 --> 01:21:24.462
"Okay, we can't, we can't take Constantinople,
so we might as well join 'em if

01:21:24.502 --> 01:21:27.862
we can't beat 'em." And they end up as

01:21:29.282 --> 01:21:33.242
probably the most famous guard in
Byzantine history, the Varangian Guard.

01:21:33.302 --> 01:21:35.761
Varangian means the men of the oath.

01:21:35.902 --> 01:21:39.782
Or the men who've sworn an
oath. This is kind of an analog

01:21:39.822 --> 01:21:41.662
of the Praetorian Guard in Ancient Rome.

01:21:42.642 --> 01:21:46.252
They were famously loyal
to the throne, but not

01:21:46.282 --> 01:21:49.692
necessarily to the person
sitting on the throne.

01:21:50.882 --> 01:21:54.642
they're major power
players. The last of the

01:21:54.682 --> 01:22:01.802
great Byzantine emperors, Basil the Bulgar
Slayer, forms them in the late 900s.

01:22:02.542 --> 01:22:05.562
And they're there with the history
all the way up until the end of it.

01:22:05.702 --> 01:22:09.262
In fact, many of our famous
Vikings, Harald Hardrada

01:22:09.462 --> 01:22:13.382
serve in the Varangian Guard. If you go to
Constantinople today, inside the Church of the

01:22:13.442 --> 01:22:17.382
Hagia Sophia, on the second
floor there's a marble balcony,

01:22:17.822 --> 01:22:21.742
and on the railings, you can find
Norse runes that are carved in by

01:22:21.802 --> 01:22:25.542
Varangian Guards who were bored
during a particularly long sermon,

01:22:26.142 --> 01:22:28.802
in a language they didn't understand,
but they had to stand there.

01:22:29.442 --> 01:22:32.662
- So that's a fascinating thing,
which is the Varangian Guard

01:22:32.802 --> 01:22:36.362
guarding the emperor of
the East Roman Empire,

01:22:36.922 --> 01:22:43.802
is made up initially, for quite
a bit of time, of Vikings.

01:22:44.422 --> 01:22:50.142
I mean, like speaking of pragmatic,
they just integrate into everything.

01:22:50.202 --> 01:22:56.192
Now eventually, the Varangian Guard
became less and less Viking over time.

01:22:56.192 --> 01:22:59.172
But this whole... You fast-forwarded
the story, we should mention

01:22:59.822 --> 01:23:07.702
that Staraya Ladoga in 753 AD is when it
was established, opening the connection to

01:23:07.762 --> 01:23:11.642
the two rivers, and they
began trading on the rivers

01:23:11.682 --> 01:23:15.592
and establishing more stable
states along the rivers,

01:23:15.642 --> 01:23:19.282
including the Kievan Rus in 862, 882,

01:23:20.142 --> 01:23:23.182
where the Varangians, so
it's the Swedish Vikings,

01:23:23.942 --> 01:23:27.542
they took Novgorod, they took Kiev,
and they established the Kievan Rus

01:23:27.551 --> 01:23:31.222
there. And that is what led to the

01:23:31.282 --> 01:23:35.012
connection to the Byzantine Empire,
where they started to... Again,

01:23:35.342 --> 01:23:39.692
the Vikings went from being Vikings.
They go through this process of trading

01:23:40.722 --> 01:23:44.282
and then establishing a state, now
they're doing treaties of different

01:23:44.342 --> 01:23:52.322
kinds, and they're also waging,
or trying to wage war. And

01:23:52.382 --> 01:23:56.272
going all the way to Constantinople,
and having a deep admiration for

01:23:56.322 --> 01:24:02.202
Constantinople, enough to then begin
to dream of sacking Constantinople.

01:24:03.042 --> 01:24:06.822
- Yeah. I mean, once they're alerted to
the wealth that's there, you know,

01:24:06.922 --> 01:24:09.662
Vikings being Vikings, they show up.

01:24:10.682 --> 01:24:15.782
- Can you speak to the Greek
Fire? So this was 941 and 944

01:24:16.882 --> 01:24:23.302
when they tried, and then Greek Fire was
this technology developed by the Romans.

01:24:23.342 --> 01:24:27.222
- We don't really know what it was,
Greek Fire. It was a form of

01:24:27.242 --> 01:24:31.022
napalm, obviously. We have the
ingredients what made it up,

01:24:31.102 --> 01:24:34.602
naphtha and oil and things like
that. But it was this very

01:24:34.662 --> 01:24:38.562
flammable material that
would ignite on contact.

01:24:38.852 --> 01:24:42.602
So the Byzantines would fill
it into clay pots and then

01:24:42.642 --> 01:24:46.372
throw the clay pots. As soon as
it's exposed to oxygen, it would

01:24:46.422 --> 01:24:50.412
start burning. They also had siphons. They
would carry, like, flamethrowers on their back

01:24:50.462 --> 01:24:54.042
and they would just spray
it at enemies. And the real

01:24:54.162 --> 01:24:57.942
devious thing about it is that if
you launch this clay pot at a ship

01:24:58.562 --> 01:25:02.412
and the material, you know,
pooled across the wood and

01:25:02.442 --> 01:25:06.362
then dripped off into the water, being oil,
it would float on top of the water and

01:25:06.442 --> 01:25:10.362
continue to burn. So that
if you were a sailor and

01:25:10.382 --> 01:25:14.022
you jumped off the ship 'cause
it's on fire and jumped into

01:25:14.082 --> 01:25:17.822
this oil patch that's on fire,
you'd be coated with it and you'd

01:25:17.902 --> 01:25:24.182
burn underneath the water. It was a horrible
way to go. So this was a state secret,

01:25:24.282 --> 01:25:28.214
closely guarded secret. So closely
guarded—it remains a mystery to this day

01:25:28.254 --> 01:25:29.954
of what exactly it was.

01:25:29.974 --> 01:25:31.014
- Which is incredible, right?

01:25:31.094 --> 01:25:34.684
- Yeah. But it, in the 944 attack on

01:25:34.714 --> 01:25:38.614
Constantinople, I mean the Vikings are coming
on their ships. They brought these ships from

01:25:38.834 --> 01:25:42.774
Sweden. I mean that's crazy.
They're in the Black Sea. They've

01:25:42.854 --> 01:25:46.614
sailed and they kind of
swarm at the Byzantines. The

01:25:46.634 --> 01:25:50.154
Byzantines launch a bunch of
decrepit old ships toward them

01:25:51.334 --> 01:25:54.374
that have Greek fire on them,
and that turns the tide. But

01:25:54.634 --> 01:25:58.034
the Byzantine emperor so
appreciates the strength of

01:25:58.094 --> 01:26:02.874
these horrifying Vikings that
he forms a bodyguard of them.

01:26:03.674 --> 01:26:07.354
- And hence we get just a few years
later, again, tried to sack

01:26:07.494 --> 01:26:09.494
Constantinople and then join them.

01:26:09.654 --> 01:26:10.214
- Join 'em, yep.

01:26:10.254 --> 01:26:14.064
- The Varangian Guard in 988
with Basil II and Vladimir,

01:26:14.794 --> 01:26:18.374
they make Varangian Guard into an
institution, and then the word of mouth

01:26:18.494 --> 01:26:22.354
spreads that this is a
real career path for the,

01:26:22.474 --> 01:26:24.914
for the Viking, is to join the guard.

01:26:25.654 --> 01:26:26.154
- Yeah, that's right.

01:26:27.014 --> 01:26:30.793
'Cause not only do you get paid
very, you're compensated very well

01:26:30.894 --> 01:26:34.734
obviously for defending the emperor, particularly if
you do a good job, but you also have opportunities

01:26:34.754 --> 01:26:37.694
'cause the emperor sends you,
"Let's go attack, you know,

01:26:39.074 --> 01:26:43.074
this tribe," and you get to keep whatever
you take. So there's tremendous amounts of

01:26:43.994 --> 01:26:48.254
war profiteering you can accomplish. And
the other great river system, the Volga,

01:26:49.254 --> 01:26:52.794
that brings you to the the great
enemy of the Byzantines, the Abbasid

01:26:52.914 --> 01:27:00.734
Caliphate. And they had a lot of trading
links with the north. So you get things

01:27:00.774 --> 01:27:06.454
like fur and amber, lots of
slaves from the from the

01:27:06.494 --> 01:27:11.574
Islamic world going up. You even
have in a Swedish coin hoard,

01:27:12.584 --> 01:27:18.374
there's a Buddha that's been
found. I mean- ... it's Sweden.

01:27:18.694 --> 01:27:24.264
- Yeah. So these networks of trade, just
how incredible are they with geography,

01:27:25.114 --> 01:27:28.134
right? You can transform
your understanding of land

01:27:28.754 --> 01:27:32.734
from the geography of the
land to the geography of the

01:27:32.774 --> 01:27:36.294
river networks, because the way
they raid and then invade and

01:27:36.313 --> 01:27:39.794
then conquer England is
through the rivers. It's an

01:27:39.834 --> 01:27:42.554
incredibly different way
of seeing the world.

01:27:42.774 --> 01:27:46.674
- Yeah. And if you look at the kingdoms the
Vikings created, I'm thinking particularly

01:27:46.714 --> 01:27:51.254
of like Eric Bloodaxe
in, you know, in York,

01:27:52.794 --> 01:27:56.634
he's controlling parts of Ireland parts of

01:27:56.694 --> 01:28:00.614
Scotland, Wales, England.
Like there's no... That

01:28:00.654 --> 01:28:05.154
doesn't make sense unless, unless
you're a Viking. You know, he's...

01:28:06.134 --> 01:28:09.974
That also added tremendously
to the terror that the

01:28:10.014 --> 01:28:13.864
Vikings brought, because I mean you
should probably be a little careful with

01:28:13.954 --> 01:28:17.874
absolute statements here, but I
can't think of a major European city

01:28:17.934 --> 01:28:19.514
that's not on a river.

01:28:20.074 --> 01:28:23.914
Uh, which meant now with the Vikings,
'cause they could travel up, you

01:28:23.974 --> 01:28:27.834
know, rivers, the shallow
rivers and then carry their

01:28:27.854 --> 01:28:31.814
boats whenever, they would, everything
was on the table now, even hundreds

01:28:31.854 --> 01:28:33.874
of miles inland is on the table.

01:28:33.974 --> 01:28:38.154
- Mm-hmm. And an incredible speed, much faster
than the land armies. It's terrifying.

01:28:38.174 --> 01:28:38.404
- It's terrifying.

01:28:38.404 --> 01:28:39.564
- So you're living in a
constant state of fear.

01:28:39.574 --> 01:28:40.374
- Constant state of fear.

01:28:41.734 --> 01:28:44.714
- We've talked about this transition

01:28:45.934 --> 01:28:49.654
in several different contexts, but
you've written about this. It's

01:28:49.694 --> 01:28:53.454
really interesting. Is
the Vikings, like Ragnar,

01:28:54.674 --> 01:29:02.574
going from this mode of sea kings with
no territory to the mode of land kings?

01:29:03.674 --> 01:29:07.514
Do you have like somebody like Harald
Bluetooth, 10th century Viking king of Denmark,

01:29:07.954 --> 01:29:11.644
you go from being these
grand explorers that are

01:29:11.714 --> 01:29:15.543
free to being state builders. Was this

01:29:15.594 --> 01:29:19.074
always inevitable for all of these
Vikings? Could we speak to the different

01:29:19.114 --> 01:29:20.634
transitions, maybe in England?

01:29:21.674 --> 01:29:25.134
- I think in one way, it's
inevitable. There's so many

01:29:25.154 --> 01:29:29.394
examples of destroyers who
just wreck civilizations.

01:29:30.894 --> 01:29:34.304
The builders are much more rare,
you know? So I think it's,

01:29:34.814 --> 01:29:38.574
it's one of the reasons I think Augustus is
a much more interesting person than Julius

01:29:38.614 --> 01:29:42.494
Caesar is. Augustus was
a builder, and I like to

01:29:42.554 --> 01:29:46.293
see that. I like to see not just can
you pull down, but can you build up?

01:29:47.534 --> 01:29:49.814
You know, just to take
Ireland for example,

01:29:50.814 --> 01:29:56.814
Dublin, Limerick, almost every major city
in Ireland was founded by the Vikings.

01:29:58.194 --> 01:30:02.114
So I don't think it's just a given that it
would have happened. I think there's something

01:30:02.174 --> 01:30:06.674
about the Vikings, and it's probably
tied to their pragmatism, their, like

01:30:07.594 --> 01:30:11.494
this pragmatic streak of, "We're gonna
use whatever. Oh, this system of

01:30:11.614 --> 01:30:14.494
king works. This taxation system's
pretty good, let's keep it."

01:30:15.294 --> 01:30:17.814
You know, "Oh, this is, this
doesn't work. Let's ditch it."

01:30:18.534 --> 01:30:21.574
- Yeah, they, I mean the,
they went from destroyer to

01:30:21.694 --> 01:30:24.934
builder very naturally and very quickly.

01:30:24.994 --> 01:30:29.514
- Yeah. There's a natural process
from conquering to building,

01:30:30.654 --> 01:30:33.434
but it does take talent and it
does take a certain something.

01:30:34.694 --> 01:30:38.674
- Can we talk about so one of the
great Vikings, Canute the Great?

01:30:39.214 --> 01:30:43.154
- I love Canute. I love Canute. I think he never,
he doesn't get his due. He's one of those

01:30:43.214 --> 01:30:46.834
unsung heroes, I think, of the
Viking world. He had a reputation.

01:30:47.294 --> 01:30:49.074
He was called the Emperor of the North.

01:30:49.874 --> 01:30:53.034
He had this massive, you
know, England, Scotland,

01:30:53.234 --> 01:30:59.374
Wales, Ireland, Norway, Sweden, Denmark.
I mean he's just tying it all together.

01:31:00.294 --> 01:31:03.434
He was an extremely
effective English king.

01:31:04.254 --> 01:31:08.794
I believe he introduced the
penny, sadly discontinued, but I—

01:31:08.874 --> 01:31:10.174
- Oh wait, really? Discontinued?

01:31:10.194 --> 01:31:11.234
- Discontinued. They're no longer making...

01:31:11.254 --> 01:31:12.224
- The penny is discontinued.

01:31:12.334 --> 01:31:14.414
- 2025's the last, the last penny.

01:31:14.814 --> 01:31:15.354
- Oh, no.

01:31:15.834 --> 01:31:18.214
- Everything's gonna go up by five.

01:31:19.994 --> 01:31:23.534
- Uh, so going to Perplexity.
Canute the Great

01:31:24.494 --> 01:31:27.914
was an early 11th century
Danish ruler who became king of

01:31:28.094 --> 01:31:31.794
England, Denmark and Norway....

01:31:31.864 --> 01:31:35.654
creating what historians call
the North Sea Empire. He's

01:31:35.754 --> 01:31:39.394
often regarded as one of the most
effective kings in Anglo-Saxon

01:31:39.454 --> 01:31:44.654
English history for stabilizing the
realm after decades of Viking warfare.

01:31:44.664 --> 01:31:47.534
Again, an example of a destroyer
becoming a state builder.

01:31:47.574 --> 01:31:52.254
- Yeah. He was, he was extremely
strong. He was effective.

01:31:53.154 --> 01:31:57.064
You know, England went from
being the whipping boy of

01:31:57.094 --> 01:32:00.414
the Vikings to controlling the Vikings.

01:32:01.434 --> 01:32:04.134
- And ended up on a pilgrimage to Rome.

01:32:04.153 --> 01:32:05.894
- Went to Rome. Yeah.

01:32:06.214 --> 01:32:11.354
- So he although a Viking war leader,
Canute ruled as a Christian king—

01:32:11.514 --> 01:32:15.434
... Patronizing churches and
monasteries and going on pilgrimage to

01:32:15.494 --> 01:32:20.394
Rome in 1027 where he attended the
Holy Roman Emperor's coronation.

01:32:21.614 --> 01:32:24.924
- Yes, he was recognized by his
contemporaries as something special, right?

01:32:24.924 --> 01:32:27.394
You don't get invited to those
coronations if you're a nobody.

01:32:28.214 --> 01:32:33.654
But the most famous story of Canute
that I know, my favorite story, is,

01:32:34.574 --> 01:32:38.554
you know, being in positions of power,
being famous, a lot of people sucking up to

01:32:38.634 --> 01:32:41.074
you, a lot of people telling you
whatever they think you wanna hear.

01:32:41.934 --> 01:32:45.784
And so people are telling him all the
time how wonderful he is, and he takes

01:32:45.814 --> 01:32:49.584
his whole court down to the
seashore and orders his,

01:32:49.654 --> 01:32:53.434
his courtiers to carry him on
his throne into the water,

