01:43:39.866 --> 01:43:43.466
Just looking at the grand picture of
the history of the Roman Empire, it's

01:43:43.666 --> 01:43:47.548
2,200 years starting from the
kingdom to the republic.... and

01:43:47.598 --> 01:43:51.078
to the imperial period, to
the East Roman Empire period.

01:43:51.618 --> 01:43:54.508
Why do societies rise and fall?

01:43:55.398 --> 01:43:59.078
- That's a really interesting question, and there are
probably as many answers as there are different

01:43:59.158 --> 01:44:06.938
kingdoms. But just the Roman Empire. My
take on it is that the collapse really

01:44:07.178 --> 01:44:14.278
starts at the end of the reign of Basil
II. So the year is 1025. Basil is the last

01:44:14.338 --> 01:44:18.258
monarch of the Macedonian dynasty, which

01:44:18.298 --> 01:44:22.188
had seen the empire
become the most powerful

01:44:22.398 --> 01:44:26.338
state in the Mediterranean, much more
powerful and advanced than its Muslim

01:44:26.358 --> 01:44:32.558
or Christian neighbors. He had expanded
the empire essentially as large as it was

01:44:32.578 --> 01:44:36.538
going to be after Justinian.
It was wealthy, it was

01:44:36.578 --> 01:44:43.178
glittering, it was educated. I mean, courtiers
had to memorize the works of Plato by

01:44:43.258 --> 01:44:47.248
heart. The emperor, one of his
favorite activities was to go, and

01:44:47.258 --> 01:44:51.198
he would begin a quote, and you would have to finish
it, but you didn't know where he would begin or

01:44:51.218 --> 01:44:52.318
what he was thinking that day.

01:44:53.258 --> 01:44:56.858
This is kind of what amused
him, so they're incredibly

01:44:56.958 --> 01:45:00.818
literate. I mean, inside Constantinople
itself, the literacy rate was

01:45:00.878 --> 01:45:02.928
close to 100, which is...

01:45:03.158 --> 01:45:06.588
... crazy. But when he died,
the court, which had been this

01:45:06.758 --> 01:45:10.748
magnificent court, this bureaucracy which
had been running the empire, and which is

01:45:10.758 --> 01:45:12.488
vital to the workings of the empire,

01:45:13.468 --> 01:45:17.358
they convinced themselves that they could run
the empire, they didn't actually need the

01:45:17.418 --> 01:45:21.278
emperor. And so they specifically
selected weak rulers,

01:45:22.018 --> 01:45:25.958
and then that led directly to the
disastrous Battle of Manzikert

01:45:25.978 --> 01:45:29.518
in 1071, where the Turks enter the story

01:45:29.978 --> 01:45:33.268
and defeat, destroy the
Roman army under Romanos

01:45:33.318 --> 01:45:37.898
Diogenes, who's attempting to break
free of the bureaucratic constraints.

01:45:38.778 --> 01:45:42.718
And then Anatolia gets flooded by these

01:45:42.778 --> 01:45:46.678
nomadic warriors, and the Byzantine
gets pushed out on the... So once

01:45:46.698 --> 01:45:50.578
they've lost the heartland, they've
lost their source of troops, they've

01:45:50.618 --> 01:45:53.958
lost their source of taxation,
they've lost their source of

01:45:54.078 --> 01:45:57.818
food. At this point it's
impossible to recover, and the

01:45:57.838 --> 01:46:01.298
crusades are an attempt, the First
Crusade anyway is an attempt

01:46:02.198 --> 01:46:03.738
by the Eastern Emperor Alexius

01:46:04.578 --> 01:46:08.358
to recover Asia Minor, more
than Jerusalem. He wants to

01:46:08.398 --> 01:46:12.318
recover Asia Minor, and obviously
it doesn't work out. So

01:46:12.358 --> 01:46:15.958
I think at that point, it's on a
trajectory that can only end in collapse.

01:46:16.728 --> 01:46:19.438
And I think that's, you can
see that same kind of thing

01:46:20.378 --> 01:46:27.578
in the Viking world that we talked about,
this stultifying, bureaucratic, this

01:46:27.658 --> 01:46:28.428
inflexibility.

01:46:29.018 --> 01:46:31.998
- Combined with the growing
threats from all directions.

01:46:32.038 --> 01:46:35.578
- Growing threats in all directions. Maybe
your own success is beginning to be a

01:46:35.618 --> 01:46:40.908
problem. And you can't adapt as quickly,
you're not as lean and mean anymore.

01:46:41.638 --> 01:46:45.038
There's too many traditions, too many, too
much, the weight of history breaks you.

01:46:45.698 --> 01:46:49.518
- You sort of mentioned the Macedonian
period, the dynasty where it's

01:46:49.718 --> 01:46:53.518
where the East Roman Empire flourished
once again, but like, they have

01:46:53.558 --> 01:46:56.258
gone through so many periods
like that, and they lasted.

01:46:56.338 --> 01:46:56.838
- That's true. That is true.

01:46:57.138 --> 01:47:01.488
- I don't know what the reason
is, but you can really

01:47:02.838 --> 01:47:05.958
trace the Roman spirit, the Roman state,

01:47:07.218 --> 01:47:11.937
the core of whatever that is,
through that 2200-year period.

01:47:12.778 --> 01:47:15.518
There's a real connection there, a
thread that connects all of it, and

01:47:16.398 --> 01:47:19.498
so that, there's lessons.
That's why we do need to

01:47:19.578 --> 01:47:24.538
study the Byzantine Empire for
lessons of what makes societies last.

01:47:24.698 --> 01:47:28.138
Eventually everything collapses,
but like that one lasted-

01:47:28.198 --> 01:47:29.418
- That one lasted a long time.

01:47:29.698 --> 01:47:33.538
- ... longer. It's easier to last when you're hidden away
somewhere, but they were in the middle of everything.

01:47:34.398 --> 01:47:35.698
Everybody wanted what they had.

01:47:35.738 --> 01:47:37.658
- Yeah, they were getting hit on all sides.

01:47:38.558 --> 01:47:42.488
There was, in their entire 2200-year
history, there was not a single year they

01:47:42.498 --> 01:47:44.318
were at peace on all frontiers.

01:47:45.138 --> 01:47:47.918
- And it wasn't always because
they were looking for trouble.

01:47:47.958 --> 01:47:47.998
- No.

01:47:48.587 --> 01:47:50.468
- They're, a lot of it is defensive.

01:47:50.678 --> 01:47:52.958
- Yep, including with those pesky Normans.

01:47:55.578 --> 01:48:01.798
- Yeah, yeah. On the topic
of great men in history,

01:48:02.298 --> 01:48:06.178
so where do you land on this great debate?
How important are individual humans

01:48:06.958 --> 01:48:11.918
versus systems? So what do you think
turns the tides of history? Can

01:48:11.978 --> 01:48:15.518
individual rulers or individual

01:48:15.638 --> 01:48:20.198
warriors or individual humans have the
power to change the course of history?

01:48:20.718 --> 01:48:21.988
- Yeah, that's the question, isn't it? I...

01:48:23.738 --> 01:48:29.378
The short answer is I subscribe to the
great man or great woman theory. Um,

01:48:30.578 --> 01:48:34.538
I think there's moments I can't imagine the Protestant
Reformation. I don't think you can just swap out

01:48:34.618 --> 01:48:38.178
Martin Luther and have a Protestant
Reformation. I don't think you can swap

01:48:38.258 --> 01:48:42.198
out Augustus and have the Roman Empire.
I mean, there are... I don't think you

01:48:42.218 --> 01:48:48.838
can swap out con- and so on and so forth.
I think ultimately these impersonal forces

01:48:48.918 --> 01:48:53.727
are insufficient for explaining,
because we are people.

01:48:53.808 --> 01:48:58.098
We are humans. We are, you know,
everything is kind of a relational thing.

01:48:58.998 --> 01:49:01.518
And but at the same time,

01:49:02.718 --> 01:49:07.748
you know, the moment needs the man, but
the man also needs the moment, you know?

01:49:07.778 --> 01:49:10.958
- Some of it is timing, some
of it is the environment—

01:49:10.998 --> 01:49:11.008
- Yeah

01:49:11.008 --> 01:49:15.618
- ... the system around it. But yeah, I've
just seen so many incredible humans

01:49:17.418 --> 01:49:21.298
that persevere through
things that would break

01:49:22.518 --> 01:49:25.858
basically everybody. And
they, the power of the

01:49:26.178 --> 01:49:29.518
belief they have. We were
talking offline about Napoleon.

01:49:30.378 --> 01:49:36.358
Here's a guy who was a student of all
the great military generals of the past.

01:49:37.298 --> 01:49:41.208
Extremely competent in being able
to micromanage every aspect of

01:49:41.238 --> 01:49:46.398
military affairs of a nation,
but also extremely confident

01:49:48.018 --> 01:49:51.318
in his vision of the world and ability

01:49:51.398 --> 01:49:55.970
to conquer anyone. And you have
the same thing with Genghis Khan.

01:49:57.410 --> 01:50:04.490
This boy that came from nothing.
Everything was taken away. He

01:50:05.990 --> 01:50:11.990
united all of Mongolia, and then conquered
most of the known world to them,

01:50:13.230 --> 01:50:18.750
including eventually China. And it's
like, well, can you possibly have

01:50:19.670 --> 01:50:24.170
the great Mongol Empire
without Genghis Khan?

01:50:24.810 --> 01:50:26.100
- No.

01:50:26.100 --> 01:50:29.830
- And the same, and we as Americans ask
ourselves that question about the

01:50:29.870 --> 01:50:33.290
founders. I mean, George
Washington, not to

01:50:33.330 --> 01:50:36.510
romanticize it, but to give
away power symbolically

01:50:37.690 --> 01:50:41.090
is a really powerful statement
like we'll mention with Augustus.

01:50:42.590 --> 01:50:47.810
There's... When somebody's
given power, and in some sense

01:50:47.990 --> 01:50:53.410
absolute power, what they do with
that power can reverberate through

01:50:53.450 --> 01:50:56.970
generations, and that's in
the hands of an individual.

01:50:57.330 --> 01:50:59.420
- Yeah. Yeah, that's exactly
right. That's well put.

01:51:00.550 --> 01:51:03.290
You know, Cincinnatus in
Ancient Rome, same thing.

01:51:05.030 --> 01:51:09.190
- What lessons from... This is a
big, ridiculous question, but-

01:51:09.640 --> 01:51:13.310
... what lessons from all the
things we've talked about, the

01:51:13.510 --> 01:51:17.860
exploration of the Vikings? What
lessons do you learn from Vikings?

01:51:17.910 --> 01:51:20.829
- Lessons, lessons to learn
from the Viking Age.

01:51:20.850 --> 01:51:24.550
- By the way, I should mention one
thing. It's a very practical lesson,

01:51:25.350 --> 01:51:28.970
That we didn't talk
about that you taught me

01:51:29.450 --> 01:51:33.190
is the, the Vikings were,
like groomed themselves.

01:51:34.050 --> 01:51:34.770
- Oh yeah, yeah.

01:51:34.790 --> 01:51:37.570
- They were like clean. This
is so very surprising to me.

01:51:38.050 --> 01:51:41.290
That they like washed themselves and
then both the men and the women-

01:51:41.590 --> 01:51:44.430
... really took care of themselves.
You don't often think about that.

01:51:44.810 --> 01:51:48.710
- There was this whole... Like,
the Vikings, everyone at this...

01:51:48.770 --> 01:51:51.610
Everyone has this very clear picture
of what a Viking looked like-

01:51:51.650 --> 01:51:55.520
... and also has no idea what a Viking
looked like somehow at the same

01:51:55.610 --> 01:51:59.340
time. Like, almost everything about
them is wrong- ... that we think of.

01:51:59.340 --> 01:52:03.330
You know, almost everything about them is
wrong. They didn't wear horned helmets.

01:52:03.430 --> 01:52:08.590
Um, they, their hair probably was
blonde disproportionately, but that

01:52:08.630 --> 01:52:12.030
was more because they used lye to
dye it because it would kill the

01:52:12.070 --> 01:52:15.890
lice. And then they would take baths on a

01:52:15.930 --> 01:52:19.790
more regular basis than... I mean,
this depended on where you were. So

01:52:19.830 --> 01:52:23.800
in England, for example, they were mocked
as being soft, which always blows my

01:52:23.870 --> 01:52:26.620
mind. Like, really? You're gonna
mock the Vikings for being soft?

01:52:26.630 --> 01:52:28.510
Because they took too many baths.

01:52:29.030 --> 01:52:32.900
But then in the Muslim east
one Muslim traveler writes

01:52:32.950 --> 01:52:37.850
that they were God's filthiest
creatures because of their habits of

01:52:39.230 --> 01:52:42.310
kind of disgusting shared bathing.

01:52:42.370 --> 01:52:44.010
- Oh, that aspect of it.

01:52:44.050 --> 01:52:47.730
Yeah. So, it's not that they didn't
bathe, they bathed a little too much and

01:52:47.770 --> 01:52:48.130
together.

01:52:48.550 --> 01:52:53.430
- They bathed, but they also
like would brush their teeth-

01:52:53.490 --> 01:52:57.290
... using like recycled water. Like, they would
then spit into a cup and pass it to the next guy.

01:52:57.330 --> 01:52:57.370
- Got it.

01:52:57.380 --> 01:52:58.810
- It was... It's not awesome.

01:52:59.290 --> 01:53:03.330
- I read that... This is, this
could be propaganda, but I read

01:53:04.430 --> 01:53:10.430
that in England there was worry that the
Vikings were a bit too attractive to the

01:53:10.530 --> 01:53:15.590
women of England because, because of how
much the Vikings took care of themselves

01:53:16.450 --> 01:53:17.910
in terms of grooming.

01:53:17.970 --> 01:53:22.610
- Yeah. In the Danelaw, like you
get invaded by these people-

01:53:22.630 --> 01:53:24.970
... they're kicking your
rear end militarily.

01:53:25.050 --> 01:53:27.830
Now they're stealing your women just
to insult you as well. You know?

01:53:28.250 --> 01:53:33.210
- Yeah. They're... They
wash themselves daily.

01:53:33.250 --> 01:53:34.920
They've got good teeth.
What is this bullshit?

01:53:34.920 --> 01:53:36.770
- Whether they need it or not,
I know. It really is...

01:53:37.710 --> 01:53:39.830
- Why you guys can't have everything?

01:53:40.010 --> 01:53:43.910
What are you doing? Anyway, I, so yeah,
so one of the lessons I think we need

01:53:43.950 --> 01:53:45.590
to draw is shower daily.

01:53:45.850 --> 01:53:46.330
- Shower daily.

01:53:46.670 --> 01:53:47.110
- Yeah, there you go.

01:53:47.120 --> 01:53:47.430
- That's right.

01:53:47.910 --> 01:53:48.830
- That's the one thing I forgot.

01:53:48.930 --> 01:53:51.610
- That's the lesson, that's the takeaway,
that's the big profound takeaway.

01:53:52.070 --> 01:53:56.510
- Is there something bigger about the
exploration, about the leaps into the unknown?

01:53:57.450 --> 01:54:00.890
- Yeah, I think a couple of years ago, there
were all these debates about statues.

01:54:00.950 --> 01:54:04.130
Make sure we pull these statues down. This person
did a bad thing, let's pull these statues.

01:54:04.170 --> 01:54:07.950
You know, and, and I always thought they were kind of
silly, too. I mean, I understand the point, but...

01:54:09.330 --> 01:54:13.190
Like, we don't... When you have a statue of
Christopher Columbus, for example, you're not

01:54:13.710 --> 01:54:17.380
glorifying every single thing the
man ever did and, and all the

01:54:17.410 --> 01:54:21.060
bad stuff that comes from
this or that. You're

01:54:21.110 --> 01:54:24.630
honoring something about him,
like the spirit it takes to

01:54:25.250 --> 01:54:29.030
cross an ocean not knowing what's
on the other side, and, and that's

01:54:29.050 --> 01:54:31.670
that spirit of exploration. I think
with the Vikings, it's the same.

01:54:32.650 --> 01:54:38.210
There's this way you, you approach
the world, this fearless, pragmatic

01:54:39.550 --> 01:54:43.030
approach. I think as an American
too, it's the ultimate,

01:54:43.450 --> 01:54:47.300
it's the ultimate rags to riches. It's the myth we
tell ourself. You know, the, the man who starts

01:54:47.330 --> 01:54:51.250
with nothing and ends up as a sea
king, well respected and sung

01:54:51.290 --> 01:54:55.390
about by poets. I mean, that's, that's
it right there. You know, this is...

01:54:57.000 --> 01:54:59.790
And when you're, when you're a
society and you stop doing this,

01:55:00.610 --> 01:55:02.089
you run into trouble as well.

01:55:03.270 --> 01:55:07.040
- Uh, what about the, the Byzantine
Empire? What lessons you draw from them?

01:55:08.180 --> 01:55:10.900
- This is a much... That's
a much bigger one. Um-

01:55:10.950 --> 01:55:11.830
- 1000-year history.

01:55:11.890 --> 01:55:15.430
- 1000-year history, and it's also
what I think is so cool about the

01:55:15.450 --> 01:55:19.230
Byzantines is that in the ways that they are
like us and the way that they are unlike

01:55:19.310 --> 01:55:24.470
us. In some ways, they're
very analogous to the United

01:55:24.510 --> 01:55:30.270
States. The kind of the polyglot nature
of their inhabitants, you know, the,

01:55:31.550 --> 01:55:36.970
their roots, the Greco-Roman,
Judeo-Christian roots. And yet

01:55:38.630 --> 01:55:41.130
it was a place of incredible alien

01:55:42.330 --> 01:55:46.110
things as well. Men sitting on top
of pillars. You know, a king, an

01:55:46.230 --> 01:55:50.690
incredibly hierarchical system
which abhorred democracy.

01:55:50.730 --> 01:55:57.786
Um, so I think it's a way, it's a
route we could have taken... um,

01:55:58.146 --> 01:56:03.086
and it's the way they handled
things. Immigration, inflation,

01:56:04.006 --> 01:56:08.826
war, peace, diplomacy. I think
there are lessons there for us.

01:56:09.306 --> 01:56:13.306
- Yeah. Yeah, I think from the Vikings,
the lessons are a bit more poetic.

01:56:13.586 --> 01:56:17.306
The lessons from the Byzantine Empire
are quite literal, like how to run a

01:56:17.346 --> 01:56:19.526
government, how to run the law, how to-

01:56:19.546 --> 01:56:21.626
- Yeah. How to build a stable society.

01:56:21.886 --> 01:56:24.646
And honestly, like you can count
on the fingers of one hand,

01:56:25.726 --> 01:56:29.726
states that have lasted a thousand years,
right? Byzantium and Venice, I think.

01:56:31.146 --> 01:56:35.096
And Venice was an offshoot of
the Byzantines. Like that's

01:56:35.166 --> 01:56:39.136
a gov- for a government to last a thousand years
is a rare thing. Like, we should be taking a

01:56:39.186 --> 01:56:44.226
look at this. Like how? And how
much of that is due to Augustus?

01:56:44.826 --> 01:56:47.366
Can we give him any credit for
this? He built the system.

01:56:48.066 --> 01:56:52.006
- Yeah. But there was a lot, like you
mentioned a lot of people along

01:56:52.046 --> 01:56:55.686
the way from Constantine to Justinian, the

01:56:55.726 --> 01:56:58.176
Basils. There's so many
emperors along the way

01:56:58.986 --> 01:57:02.956
that revolutionized and then
restabilized the empire after it

01:57:02.966 --> 01:57:03.966
was almost falling apart.

01:57:04.046 --> 01:57:08.926
- Oh, yeah. You know what else too
though? Like what happens to a human

01:57:09.766 --> 01:57:11.486
when you give that human

01:57:12.706 --> 01:57:16.536
essentially absolute power? 'Cause the
Byzantine emperor stood halfway there.

01:57:16.606 --> 01:57:20.486
I mean, he was more autocratic than
anything other than, I don't know, the pope

01:57:20.546 --> 01:57:22.885
that we, you know, have
in the modern world.

01:57:24.266 --> 01:57:28.316
What happens when you give someone that
level of power? Like, I love Justinian, but

01:57:30.206 --> 01:57:31.266
I wouldn't have liked to know him.

01:57:32.066 --> 01:57:34.266
You know, I wouldn't like
to be one of his subjects.

01:57:35.666 --> 01:57:39.506
I love Basil I, but the man was
a bloodthirsty tyrant. Like,

01:57:40.066 --> 01:57:44.046
I think it shows you what happened. What is
it? Lord Acton, "Absolute power corrupts, and

01:57:44.186 --> 01:57:48.026
absolute power corrupts absolutely." Like
that's quite clear throughout Byzantine

01:57:48.066 --> 01:57:50.966
histories, and it's a long, long list.

01:57:52.506 --> 01:57:58.046
- And as technologies become more powerful,

01:57:59.066 --> 01:58:02.996
absolute power becomes
potentially more destructive, so-

01:58:03.026 --> 01:58:04.106
- Yeah, it's more absolute.

01:58:04.326 --> 01:58:05.236
- It's more absolute.

01:58:05.326 --> 01:58:05.336
- You know?

01:58:05.336 --> 01:58:09.996
- And it's, I mean, this is the
project for the 21st century,

01:58:10.826 --> 01:58:16.866
the 20th and the 21st centuries
post-Industrial Revolution, post the computer

01:58:17.746 --> 01:58:23.946
technological revolution, post
nuclear weapons discovery.

01:58:24.026 --> 01:58:27.826
How do we construct societies
that last like the Byzantine

01:58:27.866 --> 01:58:33.986
Empire did a thousand years? It's
just like a new challenge for us.

01:58:34.026 --> 01:58:36.766
There's gonna be history
books written about us

01:58:37.666 --> 01:58:41.546
'cause like nuclear weapons,
you know, 80 years ago,

01:58:42.406 --> 01:58:49.246
it's like Greek fire that you can apply
to the entirety of human civilization.

01:58:49.286 --> 01:58:53.846
And so— ... there's gonna be good history
books, and I hope there's gonna be these

01:58:53.926 --> 01:58:57.486
stories about the American
empire, about the rest

01:58:57.686 --> 01:59:05.886
that sound similar to Byzantine Empire,
um, versus the Viking age. It only lasted-

01:59:06.026 --> 01:59:06.886
... three centuries.

01:59:07.686 --> 01:59:10.906
- I mean, I suppose the good news is it
can be done, right? Or it has been done.

01:59:11.886 --> 01:59:15.506
- It has been done. What gives you
hope about the future, having

01:59:15.586 --> 01:59:20.066
looked at the deep history
of us? What gives you hope?

01:59:21.206 --> 01:59:26.666
- During grad school, I was reading
Frederick Douglass' autobiography,

01:59:27.466 --> 01:59:33.306
and he said, "I could sit with Plato
and Cicero, and they would not flinch."

01:59:34.346 --> 01:59:38.066
You know, by which he meant that the great
conversation was for everyone, no matter what your

01:59:38.146 --> 01:59:41.966
skin color, no matter what your level of income,
and even no matter your intelligence, you know?

01:59:42.006 --> 01:59:45.746
And I think that's
actually what, that's why

01:59:46.566 --> 01:59:49.946
history comes alive for me, is
because these are not alien people.

01:59:50.286 --> 01:59:57.336
You had asked how similar are ancient
people to us psychologically.

01:59:57.336 --> 02:00:01.186
You know, and what their goals were
for life. And I think the short answer

02:00:01.246 --> 02:00:05.136
is they were identical to us, which
is why we can understand them. It's,

02:00:05.226 --> 02:00:08.766
why you should read things. It's
why you should read the Meditations

02:00:08.846 --> 02:00:10.706
because this is not just some

02:00:11.706 --> 02:00:15.535
dry whatever talking to himself
in a culture that you cannot

02:00:15.566 --> 02:00:19.646
understand and can never recreate. It's
a human talking about being human,

02:00:20.546 --> 02:00:24.326
you know? And I think human nature has not
changed, and I don't think human nature will

02:00:24.486 --> 02:00:29.496
change. So we are flawed and broken, and

02:00:31.326 --> 02:00:34.286
we're—that's the human condition.
We're gonna be flawed and broken.

02:00:35.086 --> 02:00:38.206
So I don't think... I actually
think that's the great,

02:00:39.466 --> 02:00:43.286
that's the great question of
history. If you wanna understand

02:00:43.346 --> 02:00:47.186
history, you have to know
about human nature. What is

02:00:47.226 --> 02:00:51.166
our human nature? If you think it's a blank
slate, and we can kind of educate ourselves to a

02:00:51.246 --> 02:00:54.966
utopia or, you know, like the
Marxists said then, okay.

02:00:56.006 --> 02:00:59.886
Hasn't really worked out, but okay.
If you believe we're basically bad,

02:01:01.066 --> 02:01:04.516
there's a whole set of things that come with that. If you
believe we're basically good, there's a whole set of... Right?

02:01:04.606 --> 02:01:09.706
So, you won't learn the appropriate
lesson if you misdiagnose human nature.

02:01:10.466 --> 02:01:13.706
- Yeah. I think the diagnosis
that you're kinda hinting at is

02:01:14.286 --> 02:01:17.106
seemingly the most accurate
one, which is we're flawed.

02:01:19.006 --> 02:01:22.266
A mix of good, a mix of
evil, capacity for both.

02:01:22.666 --> 02:01:26.286
- That's right. That's right. I mean,
I have to teach my kids to be

02:01:26.366 --> 02:01:30.326
kind. I don't have to teach my kids to be
unkind. I mean, one of those is natural, and

02:01:30.366 --> 02:01:35.916
one is not. I think my kids
can become kind, you know?

02:01:35.946 --> 02:01:36.816
- The capacity.

02:01:36.886 --> 02:01:37.526
- The capacity.

02:01:37.666 --> 02:01:37.696
- Is there.

02:01:37.726 --> 02:01:41.716
- Humans have the capacity
for much great things.

02:01:42.206 --> 02:01:46.006
But not perfection. It has
to come outside of us.

02:01:46.786 --> 02:01:50.006
- Well, what is it? That line of

02:01:51.286 --> 02:01:55.306
all of us are in the gutter, but some
of us are looking up at the stars.

02:01:55.706 --> 02:01:59.286
And so you gotta teach as many of us and

02:02:00.446 --> 02:02:04.166
to look up at the stars and
dream. Because once you

02:02:04.206 --> 02:02:07.686
allow yourself to dream of
a better world, you try,

02:02:08.106 --> 02:02:12.046
you try. Like the Vikings did,
go out there. Don't try to

02:02:12.086 --> 02:02:16.386
not to murder your neighbor, but if
you do, all of us have, of course.

02:02:16.826 --> 02:02:18.726
- If you do, there's Greenland.
There's Greenland.

02:02:18.766 --> 02:02:22.726
- There's Greenland. Thank you for everything you've
done for the world. Thank you for the podcast you

02:02:22.786 --> 02:02:26.746
put out there. Thank you for your incredible
books, and thank you for the conversation

02:02:26.806 --> 02:02:27.046
today.

02:02:27.666 --> 02:02:30.086
- Thank you. I really appreciate
the opportunity. Thanks a lot.

02:02:31.206 --> 02:02:35.026
- Thanks for listening to this conversation with
Lars Brownworth. To support this podcast,

02:02:35.126 --> 02:02:39.026
please check out our sponsors in the
description where you can also find links to

02:02:39.086 --> 02:02:42.066
contact me, ask questions,
give feedback, and so on.

02:02:42.946 --> 02:02:46.426
And now, let me leave you with
some words from the Volsunga Saga,

02:02:46.906 --> 02:02:50.626
a 13th century Icelandic prose
epic that tells the story

02:02:51.086 --> 02:02:56.626
of the Volsunga clan, a legendary Norse
dynasty of heroes and dragon slayers.

02:02:57.626 --> 02:03:01.686
"Fear not death, for the
hour of your doom is set,

02:03:02.506 --> 02:03:08.846
and none may escape it." And another
powerful quote from this saga is,

02:03:10.006 --> 02:03:14.426
"Better to fight and fall
than to live without hope."

02:03:16.146 --> 02:03:19.626
Thank you for listening, and
hope to see you next time.

